<HEADLINE> Gold Sale to Plunge South African Miners into </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 14 (Xinhua) -- South African mining chiefs
warned Wednesday that a million people in the country would be
plunged into misery if Britain continues selling its gold stocks.
</P>
<P>
The chiefs, beginning a three-day visit to London to challenge
Britain's bullion auction program, said they saw no reason why
Britain was rushing to sell its gold stocks, the South African
Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
They warned that the British sales would cause "atrocities" in
South Africa, the world's largest gold producer, and in
neighboring countries which provide 40 percent of the South
African mines' 230,000-strong workforce.
</P>
<P>
They listed the threat to 80,000 jobs in the industry if the
price stays the same, to another 20,000 jobs in related
industries, and the plight of neighboring countries such as
Mozambique and Lesotho.
</P>
<P>
South African government ministers are expected to join the
mining chiefs later in the week.
</P>
<P>
The visits were designed to "make the British public aware of
the British government decision".
</P>
<P>
South African mining association president Bobby Godsell and
union boss James Motlatsi denied that gold was losing its lustre
and called on the Bank of England to rethink its controversial
sales.
</P>
<P>
Godsell also cast doubt on the likelihood that the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) would proceed with its planned
sale of 300 tons of gold, designed to raise some two billion
dollars to fund debt relief for poor countries.
</P>
<P>
"We don't think they will go through with it, we don't think it
is a done deal," said Godsell, who is also president of the
Chamber of Mines which represents South Africa's major mining
houses. He was referring to impressions gained during a recent
trip to Washington.
</P>
<P>
The British and IMF selling plans have undermined gold prices
and driven them to 20-year low points. Gold was fixed on
Wednesday at 255.60 dollars an ounce in London. Last Tuesday's
British auction involved just 25 tons of gold, the first batch of
41 under the hammer in the next four years.
</P>
<P>
Godsell, who is also chief executive of Anglogold, the world's
biggest gold-mining company, questioned what "burning imperative"
has forced Britain to sell now.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair told the British parliament
that the sale was planned "on technical advice", saying "it is
entirely sensible to have reserves in a broader portfolio."
</P>
<P>
Godsell said that the U.S. Federal Reserve, the German
Bundesbank, and the Italian and French central banks had all
refused to sell gold reserves.
</P>
<P>
"The bank which is out of line is the Bank of England," Godsell
told a press briefing to kick off the visit.
</P>
<P>
The mining chiefs will try to meet politicians, trade unions,
businesses, and civil and religious groups.
</P>
<P>
"If there is no burning imperative, I would hope that they
could stop and think again," Godsell said of the Bank of England.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
