<HEADLINE> UAE Economy to Grow by 2.6 Percent in 1999: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates (UAE)
is expected to realize an economic growth of 2.6 percent in 1999,
and the growth rate might rise to 3.4 percent in the year 2000,
according to a report issued Wednesday by the Abu Dhabi Crown
Prince's Court.
</P>
<P>
The country's gross domestic product (GDP) is estimated at 50.4
billion U.S. dollars in 1999, 5.2 percent higher than the figure
last year. Its GDP will further rise to 53.4 billion dollars in
2000, says the 240-page report, which contains information on
economic and social development in the country.
</P>
<P>
The report predicts the country's per capita income to reach
17,100 dollars this year and 17,200 dollars in 2000.
</P>
<P>
The country's revenues will increase this year to 14.4 billion
dollars, of which 9.6 billion are oil revenues. Its general
expenditure is expected to be around 21.4 billion dollars to
constitute a deficit of 7 billion dollars or 14 percent of the
GDP, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It anticipates a trade surplus of 6.1 billion dollars in 1999
as exports are expected to reach 36.4 billion dollars, while
imports are projected to reach 30.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
The surplus, according to the report, is expected to rise to 7
billion dollars in 2000 as exports will increase to 39.4 billion
dollars and imports to 32.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the UAE's inflation rate will slightly
rise by 4.5 percent by the end of 1999 and remain steady in the
year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The dollar-pegged dirham's exchange rate will remain at 3.67
against the dollar in 1999 and 2000.
</P>
<P>
The UAE's population will reach 2.9 million in 1999, an
increase of 6.5 percent over 1998. The population will rise to
3.48 million in 2005 at an annual growth rate of 2.9 percent, the
report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
