<HEADLINE> Turkish Foreign Minister to Visit Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail
Cem will pay a visit to Kosovo on Saturday to tour the areas where
Turkish peace-keeping forces are deployed, Turkish sources said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish troops have been deployed in the sector of Kosovo
allocated to the united States' surveillance.
</P>
<P>
Cem will also meet with representatives of the 20,000-strong
Kosovar Turkish community which is concentrated in Pristina and
Prizren.
</P>
<P>
As a member of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO),
Turkey dispatched 11 F-16 fighter jets to participate in the
March-June NATO air strikes against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Cem will also make efforts in soothing the ongoing tension
between Kosovo's Albanian majority and the Turkish community that
faces accusations of siding with the Serbs during the war, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister's trip is a reflection of the active role
Turkey is seeking in post-war Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Turkey plans to open two offices in Pristina and Prizren in the
province, where near 1,000-strong Turkish troops have been
deployed.
</P>
<P>
The initial task of the offices will coordinate the
distribution of the humanitarian aid that Turkey will provide for
the Kosovoars under the auspices of the Turkish Red
Crescent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
