<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian President Continues Peace Effort on DRC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick Chiluba
 discussed Tuesday night in Algeria with regional leaders on how
to implement the ceasefire agreement signed here last Saturday to
end the 11- month conflict in the Democratic Republic of Congo
(DRC).
</P>
<P>
The meeting was attended by Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe,
DRC President Laurent Kabila and Namibian President Sam Nujoma as
well as foreign ministers of Angola, Rwanda and Uganda, whose
countries signed the ceasefire agreement, according to Zambia News
Agency.
</P>
<P>
No details of the meeting have been disclosed but sources said
the discussion was focused on how to work out a mechanism to make
the rebel forces fighting to topple Kabila sign the peace
agreement quickly.
</P>
<P>
The discussion was held in Algiers, capital of Algeria, where
the three-day 35th summit of the Organization of African Unity
(OAU) was held starting from Monday.
</P>
<P>
The rebels did not sign the agreement because of the
disagreement over who will sign the deal on behalf of the rebel
Rally for Democracy in Congo (RDC).
</P>
<P>
RDC split into two factions in May -- one led by Emile Ilunga
and the other by Ernest Wamba Dia Wamba.
</P>
<P>
The group led by Ilunga is firmly opposed to Wamba's signing of
the agreement but Wamba's stand is that the two factions should
both sign the agreement.
</P>
<P>
In order to continue the process, none of the rebel groups
including the Movement for the Liberation of the Congo (MLC) led
by Jean-Pierre Bemba signed the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba, who has been mandated by the Southern African
Development Community (SADC) to mediate a peaceful solution to the
war in the vast central African country, will help them resolve
the internal issue so that the rebels can sign the agreement
later.
</P>
<P>
The three rebel groups have said that they will not be bound by
the agreement because they did not sign it.
</P>
<P>
Bemba said Wednesday that his forces have been fighting with
the government forces every day since the ceasefire agreement was
signed.
</P>
<P>
Kabila also said in a radio interview Tuesday that the war is
continuing but he added that he is confident that peace will
eventually take hold. 
</P>
</TEXT>
