<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Annan Not to Abandon Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 14 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan Wednesday left Algeria for a visit to Slovakia, winding up
his six-nation Africa tour at a time when African leaders and
people are groping for ways to end armed conflict and promote
economic development.
</P>
<P>
Beginning July 6, the trip, which took him to Senegal, Sierra
Leone, Liberia, Guinea, Nigeria and Algeria, has sent a strong
message to the world: the United Nations is not giving up Africa
although the Organization has met with its peacekeeping failure in
Angola.
</P>
<P>
Annan started the trip against a backdrop of speculations that
the United Nations would abandon Africa after it shut down the
decade-old peacekeeping operations and complaints from some
African countries that African conflicts were overshadowed at the
world body by the Kosovo issue.
</P>
<P>
The visit came on heels of the signing of peace accords for
Sierra Leone and the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC), although
rebels have so far refused to sign the latter deal. More
encouraging signs were the second successful post-apartheid
elections in South Africa, the African economic power, and smooth
transition to civilian rule in Nigeria, Africa's most populous
country.
</P>
<P>
"The overall picture in Africa today is nowhere near as gloomy
as it seems to those elsewhere," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, however, deadly conflicts persist: in Angola,
in the DRC, and between Ethiopia and Eritrea. Along with conflict,
in the past year the world also witnessed, in the Comoros,
Guinea-Bissau and Niger, new examples of a problem emerged -- the
duly-elected governments were overthrown by force.
</P>
<P>
Annan "is very concerned that the many crises in Africa give
the whole continent a bad name," said U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard,
who is with the U.N. chief on his Africa and Europe tour.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Africa, Annan, a Ghanaian, also attended the
Organization of Africa Unity (OAU) summit, the century's last
session, in Algeria, which offered him good opportunities to talk
with OAU and African leaders on how to bring an end to on-going
conflicts and boost economic advancement on the war-torn
continent.
</P>
<P>
"The United Nations will continue to do what we can to bring
about an end to those hostilities," Annan told African leaders.
"The development of Africa has always been one of the United
Nations prime concerns, and with good reason: healthy development
is the best long-term conflict prevention we know."
</P>
<P>
Annan, the first black African who heads the 185-nation world
body, presented what was termed as a comprehensive report to the
Security Council, in April last year, shedding more light on the
causes and effects of African conflicts, and how to promote
economic growth in the war-ravaged Africa.
</P>
<P>
Annan has called upon African countries to refrain from weapons
purchase in order to save more money for development, and appealed
to Western countries for a quick debt relief and more investment.
</P>
<P>
With Annan at the helm, the United Nations is undertaking more
efforts to help Africa out of conflicts and poverty, and back on
the tracks to prosperity.
</P>
<P>
In Western Sahara, United Nations officials are continuing
their efforts to arrange a referendum. And in the Central African
Republic, the United Nations has mounted a multi-dimensional
peacekeeping operation responsible for organizing elections,
disarmament and other things.
</P>
<P>
Annan will dispatch three U.N. officials to Lusaka, capital of
Zambia, to persuade DRC rebels to sign the peace accord, a U.N.
spokesman announced here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Annan has led the United Nations, including the Security
Council, in rendering pains-taking efforts to beef up
conflict-preventing and peacekeeping capacities in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation Security Council is expected to discuss the U.N.
peacekeeping presence in the DRC after rebels sign the peace
agreement.
</P>
<P>
During Annan's Africa visit, "he has met with African leaders
he wants to contact, and he went to see refugees in a first-hand
way, in order to see what he can do from his position as the
Secretary-General to help Africa," Manoel de Almeida e Silva, the
U.N. spokesman, told Xinhua. 
</P>
</TEXT>
