<HEADLINE> France to Increase Oil Import From Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Due to upward trend in crude prices
on the international market, France has decided to increase its
oil import from Angola starting from this year, which is believed
to improve the trade balance between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Robert Igier, economic counsellor of the French embassy in
Angola, said here Wednesday that 99 percent of the country's
import of oil products form Angola will be crude oil.
</P>
<P>
France's export to Angola accounts for 93 percent of the total
volume of bilateral trade. About 70 percent of the export are
industrial equipment, whereas 23 percent are agricultural
products, said Igier.
</P>
<P>
Since 1995, the bilateral trade has been in favor of France,
at 116 million U.S. dollars in 1998.
</P>
<P>
France has been the third largest product supplier to Angola
traditionally, but last year its position was challenged by South
Africa. Meanwhile, Angola has been France's second largest trade
partner in southern Africa, after South Africa.
</P>
<P>
France and Angola have just signed several big-sum agreements
on oil exploitation, therefore the French official feels
optimistic about the prospects of bilateral trade in the coming
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
