<HEADLINE> Greek, Albanian, Macedonian Foreign Ministers Hold Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The foreign ministers of Greece,
Albania and Macedonia Wednesday agreed on the drafting of programs
of cooperation in border security, tackling illegal migration,
economy, culture and environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
The decision came after Greek Foreign Minister George
Papandreou and his Albanian and Macedonian counterparts, Paskal
Milo and Aleksander Dimitrov, held their first tripartite meeting
at the Agios Achillios islet in the northern Greek region of
Prespes, the semi-official Athens News Agency (ANA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Papandreou said that such programs would include the creation
of an ecological park in the Prespes district, the promotion of
ecotourism, and the creation of a free circulation zone for the
citizens of the three countries.
</P>
<P>
He also said that Greece wanted to submit at the informal
European summit in Tampere, Finland, a proposal for promotion of
cooperation between the three countries in the framework of EU
stabilization plans for the Western Balkans.
</P>
<P>
The three ministers agreed to meet next in Ohrid, a lakeside
resort in Macedonia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
