<HEADLINE> South Africa Opens Embassy in Algeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The South African embassy in
Algiers, Algeria, was officially opened by Foreign Minister
Nkosazana Zuma Wednesday, according to the South African Foreign
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
"Algeria's invaluable contribution to the struggle for freedom
in South Africa has paved the way for close cooperation between
our two countries," Zuma was quoted by a ministry statement as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Recalling the long-standing ties between the two countries, she
said that it was now important to turn the political goodwill into
concrete benefits for the people of both countries.
</P>
<P>
Zuma also recalled that Algerian President Abdelaziz
Bouteflika, in his then capacity as president of the United
Nations General Assembly, was instrumental in expelling the South
African apartheid regime from the world body in 1974.
</P>
<P>
This historical event had set the course for all South Africans
to attain their freedom and dignity, said Zuma.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said the bilateral commission established
between the two countries in 1995 had formed a solid foundation
for greater economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Already there were numerous South African companies doing
business in Algeria, particularly in the mining and manufacturing
industries, she noted.
</P>
<P>
Zuma was accompanying South African President Thabo Mbeki in
Algiers for the 35th summit of the Organization of African Unity,
which ended here Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
