<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Urged to Attract Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government should
create an enabling environment to help the country to attract much
needed foreign investment, a high-ranking official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Pat Rooney, chairman of industrial task force of the National
Economic Consultative Forum, said the country was in need of
foreign currency inflows when presenting a paper on industrial
development into the new millenium at the opening of a three-day
confederation of Zimbabwe Industries Congress.
</P>
<P>
"There is need for a concerted effort between the government
and the private sector to improve the negative image the country
is facing if our industries are to successfully contribute to the
stabilization of the economy," he said.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's economy was characterized by high interest rates,
lack of local investment, declining exports, minimal direct
foreign investment and static employment.
</P>
<P>
Rooney said one of the task force's objective was to attain an
industrial growth rate of 2.5 percent of the projected gross
domestic product.
</P>
<P>
"This goal can only be achieved if the environment is conducive
to investors," he said.
</P>
<P>
He urged local companies to improve their managerial and
technical skills to make sure that their products were competitive
both on regional and global markets.
</P>
<P>
"Zimbabwe has the potential of being the most competitive
country in the southern African region," he said, adding, "as a
result we need to increase our development programs so that we can
keep up with international standards."
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the balance of payments support of
the International Monetary Fund (IMF) would help stabilize the
economy within the next six to 12 months.
</P>
<P>
"Although we welcome the IMF monetary support, industrialists
should start looking at the future and work toward
self-sufficiency for the long- term benefits," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
