<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Inflation Reaches Record High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's July year-on-year
inflation reached a new record high of 55.2 percent, gaining 2.2
percentage points on the June rate of 53 percent, the Central
Statistical Office (CSO) said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The month-on-month rate of inflation for June was 1.9 percent,
gaining 0. 5 percentage points on the May rate of 1.4 percent,
which means the prices as measured by the all items consumer price
index increased by an average of 1. 9 percent from May, 1999 to
June 1999.
</P>
<P>
The Central Statistical Office said purchasing power had gone
down such that a dollar today was equivalent to 10.2 cents in
1990.
</P>
<P>
"The headline inflation of 55.2 percent is an all time high,"
said the office, adding "it comes at a time when recent maize
meal price increases to be completely factored into the consumer
price index for the month ending July, is likely to increase
inflation further," said the office. 
</P>
</TEXT>
