<HEADLINE> Tehran Protests Against Remarks by Turkish PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Ministry on
Wednesday summoned Turkish Charge D'affaires to Tehran Kut Sezgin
to protest the remarks of Turkish Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit on
the recent unrest in Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Head of the ministry's mass media department termed Ecevit's
remarks as "irresponsible" and "against the principle of good
neighborliness," the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit said on Tuesday the current violent unrest in Iran is a
result of an "oppressive and outdated" Islamic regime and the
Iranian people cannot be expected to endure it for a long period.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian official requested Sezgin to offer explanation on
the issue and inform senior Turkish officials of Iran's protest.
</P>
<P>
Sezgin said Ankara is interested in strengthening its ties with
Tehran and he will inform his government of Iran's protest.
</P>
<P>
During the past week, Iran experienced the worst unrest
since the 1979 Islamic revolution as security forces clashed
with protesting students following an unauthorized police
crackdown on the Tehran University dormitory complex on Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
The police assault, a response to a student rally protesting
the approval of a new press law and the closure of the leading
moderate daily Salam (Hello), has been widely condemned in the
Islamic Republic.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a massive rally on Wednesday, Secretary of the
Iranian Supreme National Security Council (SNSC) Hassan Rowhani
also warned foreign countries against voicing support for the
unrest in Tehran.
</P>
<P>
"Speeches made by certain countries about the events of the
past several days will be recorded in our files," said
Rowhani, also Vice Majlis (parliament) speaker.
</P>
<P>
"We will give them an appropriate answer at the opportune
time," he added. 
</P>
