<HEADLINE> Ethio-Eritrean Conflict Spills Over to Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Large convoys of Ethiopian
troops have been seen crossing the border with Somalia, chasing
the Oromo-ethnic militiamen opposing to the Ethiopian government,
reports reaching here said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The reports said that three convoys of Ethiopian troops,
estimated at over 5,000 carrying heavy military hardware, passed
through several towns and villages in Gedo and Bay regions in the
past two days.
</P>
<P>
According to civilians arriving from Gedo Wednesday, the
Ethiopian troops who are being accompanied by some Somalis are
trying to capture the tarmac airport of Ballidogleh controlled by
faction leader Hussein Mohamed Aidid.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopians are also reportedly trying to attack Qoryoley
town which has been the site chosen by Aidid for military base for
the Oromo soldiers fighting against Prime Minister Meles Zenawi's
administration in Addis Ababa.
</P>
<P>
There has been no single resistance reported against the
Ethiopian convoys in any of those towns or villages.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Somali National Front faction which dominates
Gedo region has also confirmed the new Ethiopian soldiers moving
deeply into Somalia.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman of the faction, Ibrahim Juama Howleh, said that his
faction is ready to open dialogue with Ethiopia and settle their
differences peacefully.
</P>
<P>
There is no immediate comment on the developments from the
Ethiopian government.
</P>
<P>
Both Ethiopia and Eritrea are allegedly supplying weapons,
ammunition and even soldiers to some Somali factions with the aim
of undermining the other's power.
</P>
<P>
The two Horn of Africa neighbors resorted to arms over a
disputed part of border in early last May. Despite efforts made
by the international community, there is in sight no immediate end
to the conflict between the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
