<HEADLINE> 3 Iraqi Civilians Injured in Air Raids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Three Iraqi civilians were
injured on Wednesday in U.S. and British warplanes bombardment of
some civilian and military targets, an Iraqi military spokesman
announced.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman was quoted by the Iraqi News Agency as saying
that at 10:35 (0635 GMT) eight formations of enemy warplanes
coming from Turkish airspace violated northern Iraqi airspace over
Dohuk, Erbil and Neineva provinces.
</P>
<P>
These enemy warplanes bombed some civilian installations in
the area, leading to the injuries of three civilians, said the
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He said that Iraqi air defenses fired back and forced the
enemy planes to flee to their base in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that since the U.S. and Britain launched
airstrikes against Iraq last December, their warplanes have made
9,994 sorties over the no-fly zones in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-led western allies imposed the no-fly zones in
Iraq in the wake of the 1991 Gulf War with the claimed aim
of protecting the Kurds in the north and the Shiite Muslims
in the south from possible attacks by the Iraqi government
troops.
</P>
<P>
Since last December's bombardment of Iraq, U.S. and British
warplanes have been regularly attacking Iraqi civilian and
military targets, causing severe civilian casualties and property
damages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
