<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commentary: Africa Striving for Peace, Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, July 14 (Xinhua) -- African leaders gathered here on
July 12-14 with a new openness and pragmatism to scrutinize the
daunting challenges facing the continent at the turn of the
millenium and try to map out a blueprint for the future.
</P>
<P>
Algerian President Abdelaziz Bouteflica, the host of the
meeting, called the largest ever gathering of African leaders as a
new start for the continent.
</P>
<P>
The 46 heads of state and government, who participated in the
35th summit of the Organization of African Unity (OAU), shared
unanimous views that peace and development are, more than ever,
two things that Africans have been yearning for.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo called on leaders of
African countries in his keynote address at the summit to make
"2000 a year of peace and security in Africa," saying "Africa's
reputation as a continent at war against itself must be arrested."
</P>
<P>
The leaders fervently believe that Africa is in dire need of
peace, a prerequisite for healthy and sustainable development.
Without peace, development would be nothing but a dream and Africa
would continue to be marginalized and eventually swallowed by the
increasingly high wave of globalization.
</P>
<P>
At a time when peace and development have constituted the
mainstream of the world, many parts of Africa are still
experiencing the scourge of domestic upheavals, border conflicts
and regional wars.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo said: "If the 1980s was Africa's lost decade
economically, the 1990s has turned out to be the decade when
conflicts have reached an ominous proportion."
</P>
<P>
More than 30 conflicts have taken place in the poor continent
since 1970s and at least 14 African countries are still directly
or indirectly embroidered in ravaging wars.
</P>
<P>
The civil war in the Democratic Republic of Congo made the
fragile peace process in the Great Lakes region more shaky.
</P>
<P>
The on-and-off war in the Horn of Africa cost so many innocent
lives and inflicted unbearable suffering to people there.
</P>
<P>
Constant conflicts have not only posed a colossal threat to the
 continent's stability, but also driven millions of people
homeless and local economies stagnated.
</P>
<P>
Driven by wars slipping out of control bit by bit, some African
 governments have to dump their hard-earned scanty foreign
exchange into the bottomless abysses of war and even run the risk
of killing their faltering economies.
</P>
<P>
Africa is already trudging under a staggering burden of a
350-billion- dollar foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
What is more, the figure is growing at a surprisingly high rate
of 23 percent each year, making it a sure thing that any more
burden, however small it is,

would crush the backbones of the economy.
</P>
<P>
Faced with these daunting challenges, African leaders stand up
to embrace them and try to restore peace in the war-torn
continent.
</P>
<P>
With their own efforts and collective wisdom, they struck out
peace deals to end the year-long wars both in the Democratic
Republic of Congo and Sierra Leone by bringing the warring parties
to the negotiation table.
</P>
<P>
The warring sides of the Sudan civil war have agreed to meet in
Nairobi later this month, and the OAU summit has persuaded
belligerent Ethiopia and Eritrea to renew their peace talks.
</P>
<P>
U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees Sadako Ogata told reporters
at the sidelines of the summit, "I think that there is genuine
attempt to share problems and see what they can do with each other
about solving them."
</P>
<P>
The African heads of state, who are highly praised by diplomats
and observers for their openness and pragmatism, have decided to
get down to analyze various causes of war and get rid of them so
that the continent could strive for a quick recovery and an even
economic take-off.
</P>
<P>
Peace is the precondition to development and development
guarantees peace. At the summit, the statesmen also decided to
further strengthen economic cooperation between member states and
hasten the pace of the establishment of African Economic
Community.
</P>
<P>
They realized that to enhance the competitiveness of African
economy in the world, the only way out is to reverse the growing
trend of Africa's marginalization in the international arena.
</P>
<P>
The three-day summit has ended with a declaration pressing for
peace and development, the conspicuous theme of this epoch-making
gathering of African leaders.
</P>
<P>
With newly set goals in mind, the leaders will work tirelessly
for the bright future looming ahead and make Africa better
prepared for the new millennium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990715.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
