<HEADLINE> Tanzanian President to Visit Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President Benjamin William
Mkapa on Thursday starts a three-day official visit to Egypt,
Tanzanian ambassador in Cairo Muhamed Mwinyi Mzale said on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Mzale told Egypt's Middle East News Agency that Mkapa's visit
is aimed at fostering bilateral relations in all domains,
especially in the economic and trade areas, Mzale said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the visit will afford "a good opportunity" to
the two leaders to take up issues on the bilateral ties,
particularly to activate the Tanzanian-Egyptian Joint Committee
formed in 1986.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian diplomat asserted that the two countries enjoy
historical cooperations and share views on regional and
international issues.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa will reiterate support for Mubarak's efforts to bring
peace to the Middle East and Africa, Mzale said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt was the first Arab country to make peace with Israel by
signing a peace treaty in 1979. It has played a key role in
mediating the Arab-Israeli peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Cairo is also keen on seeking solutions to the conflicts on the
African continent, including the civil war in the Democratic
Republic of Congo, the border disputes between Eritrea and
Ethiopia and the civil war in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Mkapa is expected to meet with Egyptian
businessmen in a bid to allure them to invest in Tanzania and
promote bilateral trade, the Tanzanian ambassador said. 
</P>
