<DOCNO> XIE19990715.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 071450   Concerted Efforts Urged for Peace in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, July 14 (Xinhua) -- African countries were urged here
Wednesday to make concerted efforts to establish stable state
institutions to promote the use of peaceful means in solving
conflicts on the continent.
</P>
<P>
The call was contained in the Algiers Declaration issued at the
end of the 35th summit of the Organization of African Unity (OAU),
which was seen as a historical meeting for the continent at the
turn of the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
While hailing the passing 20th century as a century that has
been brought to a successful conclusion through decolonizing the
continent, the declaration reaffirmed the determination of African
leaders to solve conflicts in conformity with the principles of
sovereign equality, non- interference, non-resort to threats or
the use of force.
</P>
<P>
The safeguarding of independence, sovereignty and territorial
integrity of each state, treasured as the source of power at the
founding of OAU back in 1963, were also reaffirmed as basic
principles of the continental bloc.
</P>
<P>
The OAU mechanism for conflict prevention, management and
resolution was taken as a "valuable asset" for Africa, said the
declaration.
</P>
<P>
While praising the contributions of the founding fathers for
the decolonization of the continent, the declaration said OAU has
played an irreplaceable role in the affirmation of political
identity and the realization of unity for Africa.
</P>
<P>
It called on Africans to continue to make OAU a vital
instrument of Africa's collective action both within the continent
and in their relations with the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
The achievement in winning freedom and independence, the
declaration said, constitutes for Africans a source of profound
and legitimate pride.
</P>
<P>
Despite the hopes generated by the end of the Cold War, the OAU
document said, African leaders find that post-Cold War era is
fraught with "new and grave uncertainties, serious risks of
marginalization and new challenges that pose numerous threats to
the continent."
</P>
<P>
Globalization, the elimination of weapons of mass destruction,
terrorism, among others, were listed as the challenges facing
Africa in the 21st century.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990715.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ban On British Beef Exports Lifted Worldwide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission Wednesday
announced the decision to lift a three-year ban on British beef
exports from August 1.
</P>
<P>
The European Union (EU)'s executive said the decision was made
under the Date Based Export Scheme (DBES), which applies only to
deboned meat and meat products obtained from animals born after
August 1, 1996.
</P>
<P>
According to the DBES, the animals slaughtered must be over six
months and under 30 months of age.
</P>
<P>
The scheme also includes the slaughter and destruction of
offspring from Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy (BSE) affected
cows. And verification that the dam of the animal concerned has
been alive six months after birth and not developed BSE, known as
mad cow disease.
</P>
<P>
The application of a BSE test under the DBES is not considered
as it would serve no useful purpose, the European Commission said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The decision is expected to end a worldwide embargo on British
beef sales which is said to have cost the farming industry about
2 billion U.S. dollars in lost sales. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
