<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- Yemeni and Egyptian businessmen started contacts on
the implementation of an agreement signed during the recent Cairo
session of the higher joint committee between the two countries on
the initiation of the Al-Yamamah United Bank.
</P>
<P>
The capital of the bank amounts to 100 million U.S. dollars, 20
million of which are a paid-in capital.
</P>
<P>
The joint bank will follow the banking regulations of Yemen,
daily Al-Hayat Wednesday quoted Egypt's Ambassador in Sanaa
Mahmoud Murtadah as saing.
</P>
<P>
It will be based in Sanaa and have branches in Egypt and other
countries as well as in Yemen. It will contribute the development
of joint ventures between the two countries, Murtadah added.
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- Syrian Minister of State for Planning Abdel Rahim
Al-Soubei and Japanese Ambassador in Damascus Takishi Kagami signs
Wednesday an accord under which Japan will provide a grant of 969
million yen (8 million U.S. dollars) to Syria, Al-Hayat said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The grant will be used in the rehabilitation works of Banias
Power Plant which was launched with a Japanese official funding.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The capital of the companies in Egypt that began
production last June stood at 866 million Egyptian pounds (254.71
million dollars), an investment official said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The figure represented an increase of 7.97 percent over the
same period last year, Chairman of the General Authority for
Investment and Free Zones Ibrahim Fawzi was quoted by Egypt's
Middle East News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Minister of the Public Business Sector Atef
Ebeid said on Tuesday that the proceeds from privatizing public
enterprises have amounted to 11.5 billion pounds (3.38 billion
dollars) since 1995.
</P>
<P>
Of the proceeds, some 6 billion pounds (1.76 billion dollars)
were funds for settling the debts of the privatized companies, 1.5
billion pounds (441.18 million dollars) for early retirement of
employees and 4 billion pounds (1.18 billion dollars) put in the
state coffers.
</P>
<P>
Ebeid said 12 more companies will be offered for sale before
September. 
</P>
