<HEADLINE> Lebanon Marks Lebanese Prisoners' Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Human rights groups and unions
across Lebanon Wednesday held various activities to mark the
Lebanese Prisoners' Day.
</P>
<P>
The day was set on July 14, 1983 when Israel established the
first jail in south Lebanon to hold Lebanese who were accused of
involving in actions against Israeli forces in the region.
</P>
<P>
The country's National Committee for Lebanese Held in Israeli
Prisons staged a sit-in in front of the United Nations' building
in downtown Beirut.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators said they had submitted an appeal to
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, Arab League Secretary-General
Ahmed Esmat Meguid and international human rights organizations.
</P>
<P>
The statement demanded that every prisoner held in Israeli
jail be released and Israel stop ill-treating prisoners and give
the victims compensations.
</P>
<P>
Similar protests were held in other cities and areas of the
country.
</P>
<P>
About 130 people are being held without trial in the Khiam
prison in the Israel-occupied border zone in south Lebanon where
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in 1985 allegedly to
protect its north from Lebanese guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
The prison, which is run by the pro-Israeli South Lebanon Army
under Israeli supervision, has been condemned by international
human rights groups for torturing prisoners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
