<HEADLINE> First Arab-Israeli Appointed to Sensitive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 14 (Xinhua) -- For the first time in Israel's
51-year history, an Arab-Israeli legislator was appointed
Wednesday to sit on the semi-secret Foreign Affairs and Defense
Committee of the Knesset (parliament).
</P>
<P>
The United Arab List, one of the three Arab parties in the
Knesset, chose its member Hashem Mahameed to the prestigious
committee which oversees national security and foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
Dovish Justice Minister Yossi Beilin called the appointment of
Mahameed a "historic event" and another step toward making the
Arab community a legitimate part of the Israeli society.
</P>
<P>
Arabs make up about 18 percent of Israel's 6 million
population, but they feel discriminated in almost every field
because of the Israeli-Arab conflict.
</P>
<P>
In the May 17 prime ministerial election, the Arab electorate
voted almost unanimously for Ehud Barak, who has promised to
improve the situation of the Arab society and ensure their right
of equality.
</P>
<P>
But when forming his broad-based coalition government, Barak
failed to break the half-century taboo in Israel that excludes
Arab from the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
After Mahameed's appointment, the right-wing Likud announced
that it would submit a no-confidence motion against the government
and would boycott the work of the committee.
</P>
<P>
At an emergency news conference, former Likud defense minister
Moshe Arens said Mahameed should not sit on the sensitive
committee because he is not interested in Israel's security,
citing his anti-defense establishment attitude and sympathy for
the Islamic militant group Hamas.
</P>
<P>
Likud member Uzi Landau, former chairman of the committee,
accused Barak of currying favor with the Arabs at the expense of
Israel's national security.
</P>
<P>
Mahameed dismissed all these allegation, saying he has the
right to be on the committee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990715.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.Irish Assembly Ordered to Convene Thursday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The British Government Wednesday
issued an order for a new Northern Ireland assembly to convene
Thursday in Belfast, thus formally setting in progress the next
major step in the Good Friday peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
"Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam has directed the assembly
to meet tomorrow morning at 10.30 a.m. Thursday," a Reuters
reported quoted a spokesman for her office as saying.
</P>
<P>
The go-ahead for the all-party assembly to meet was given while
negotiations were still going on to convince Protestant
politicians they should take part in the devolution of power from
London to the new Belfast government which would include
Catholics.
</P>
<P>
Protestant politicians are meeting later Wednesday to decide if
they can take part in the assembly and accept a deal by Britain
and Ireland to implement the so-called Good Friday peace plan
despite a row over guerrilla disarmament by the Irish Republican
Army (IRA), according to local media reports.
</P>
<P>
One of the scheduled first orders of business for the
108-member assembly would be the appointment of ministers.
</P>
<P>
Under the peace deal, the Ulster Unionist Party (UUP) of First
Minister David Trimble would get three posts, the moderate
Catholic Social Democratic and Labor Party (SDLP) would get three,
the hardline Protestant Democratic Unionist Party (DUP) would get
two and Sinn Fein, political ally of the IRA, would get two posts.
</P>
</TEXT>
