<HEADLINE> Crude Oil Sets New High With Dipping U.S. Inventories </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- World oil markets stampeded to
another high Wednesday amid fresh evidence from the United States
that OPEC export limits are swiftly erasing excess petroleum
stockpiles in the West.
</P>
<P>
London August futures for benchmark Brent crude traded to a
20-month peak of 19.43 a barrel following a weekly American
Petroleum Institute report on U.S. oil inventories.
</P>
<P>
But Brent shed some gains, trading two cents up on the day at
19.05 U.S. dollars as speculators pocketed profits from a five
U.S. dollar rally over the past six weeks.
</P>
<P>
The API said U.S. gasoline and crude oil stocks declined
further than expected in the week to July 9 and confirmed that
U.S. demand was growing faster than previously projected.
</P>
<P>
"Further upside impetus has been seen with the API report again
on the positive side," Reuters quoted Lawrence Eagles of brokers
GNI as saying.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said oil's latest surge had been underpinned by the
perception that OPEC exporters will maintain a tight rein on
supplies, despite fears that the market might overheat. 
</P>
