<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Globalization Challenges Africa: OAU Declaration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Globalization is the "most
widespread challenge" Africa is facing in the new millennium,
according to the Algiers Declaration issued here Wednesday at the
closing of the 35th summit of the Organization of African Unity
(OAU).
</P>
<P>
The declaration said globalization has aroused fears that it
may pose serious threats to the sovereignty, cultural and
historical identities and gravely undermines the prospect of
development for Africa.
</P>
<P>
Globalization should be placed within the framework of a
democratically conceived dynamics, and implemented "collectively
to make it an institution capable of fulfilling the hope for a
concerted development of mankind and prosperity shared by all
peoples," the declaration said.
</P>
<P>
The growing marginalization of the United Nations and its role
for the maintenance of international peace and security and the
promotion of international cooperation for development, is the
challenge second only to globalization for Africa.
</P>
<P>
African heads of state and government agreed that the
unilateral use of force in international relations, outside the
duly conferred mandate of the U.N. Security Council, opens the way
to practices inimical to world peace and security.
</P>
<P>
They also called for respect toward U.N. role and
responsibilities in the maintenance of international peace and
security.
</P>
<P>
For this end, said the declaration, a genuine democratization
of international relations based on the active participation and a
balanced consideration of the legitimate concerns of all nations
should be in place in the world.
</P>
<P>
It stressed the need for democratization equally applied to
other international institutions including, particularly, the
International Monetary Fund and the International Bank for
Reconstruction and Development.
</P>
<P>
Nuclear disarmament, and the elimination of other weapons of
mass destruction, terrorism, drug trafficking and organized crimes
were listed as other challenges facing the continent.
</P>
<P>
The final document of the 35th OAU summit urged the continent
to enter the third millennium with a genuine spirit of
cooperation, restored human dignity and a common hope in an
inter-dependent future for mankind. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
