<HEADLINE> Blair Agrees to Change N. Ireland Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
announced Wednesday that his government is to table amendments to
the Northern Ireland Bill in a bid to meet Unionist and opposition
Conservative concerns.
</P>
<P>
"We will table amendments in line with the Good Friday
Agreement," Blair told parliament a few hours before the Ulster
Unionist Party executive was to meet in Belfast to give its
verdict on the plan.
</P>
<P>
Blair said that the amendments would ensure that the
decommissioning of paramilitary weapons happened in accordance
with a strict timetable.
</P>
<P>
The changes would also allow for the formal identification of
any parties that defaulted in the process and for the suspension
of the institutions set up by Northern Irish devolution.
</P>
<P>
Blair indicated he was still hoping the unionists, deeply
suspicious of the proposals, would agree in time for a devolved
government to be set up in Belfast later this week.
</P>
<P>
The emergency legislation to save the Northern Irish peace
process, passed by Britain's House of Commons early Wednesday, is
being debated in the House of Lords. 
</P>
