<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Wholesale Prices Fall 0.1 percent in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Labor Department said
Wednesday that wholesale prices dropped 0.1 percent in June, the
first decline in four months, due to the falling prices for
gasoline and cars.
</P>
<P>
The June decline in the Producer Price Index followed a 0.2
percent increase in May and was the first decline since a 0.5
percent plunge in February.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the moderation in wholesale prices, if matched at
the retail level, will likely boost the confidence of Fed
officials that they do not need to move quickly to raise interest
rates and slow economic growth.
</P>
<P>
During the first six months of this year, wholesale prices have
been increasing at an annual rate of 1.5 percent. But wholesale
prices had shown no increase at all for all of 1998, because that
good performance reflected the impacts of the global financial
crisis, which depressed demand and prices for many commodities
including oil.
</P>
<P>
For the first six months of this year, energy prices rose at an
annual rate of 13.5 percent, a sharp turnaround from a 9.1 percent
rate of decline in the final six months of 1998.
</P>
<P>
In both May and June, energy prices moderated after a huge, 5.1
percent spurt in April. Energy prices dipped 0.3 percent in June,
reflecting a 1.9 percent fall in gasoline prices. Gasoline costs
had been down an even bigger 2.7 percent in May.
</P>
<P>
While rising demand during the summer driving season has pushed
gasoline pump prices back up in recent weeks, analysts said they
were not looking for further huge increases in the months ahead as
supplies should remain plentiful.
</P>
<P>
June's food costs were up 0.4 percent at the wholesale level, a
slight moderation after a 0.5 percent rise in May. Beef prices
soared 8.2 percent last month, the biggest one-month jump since an
8.8 percent increase in October 1985.
</P>
<P>
But the big increase in beef was offset somewhat by a 5.2
percent decline in pork prices, the biggest decrease in this
category in 11 months. Vegetable prices were up 14.5 percent with
the gains led by big jumps in the price of cauliflower, tomatoes,
broccoli and celery.
</P>
<P>
Outside the volatile food and energy sectors, the so-called
core rate of inflation at the wholesale level fell 0.2 percent in
June, the first decline since 0.2 percent in January.
</P>
<P>
The drop in the core rate of inflation reflected a big, 1.3
percent fall in the price of passenger cars, the biggest reversal
since January's 1.4 percent dip, and a 0.7 percent decline in the
category that includes sport utility vehicles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990715.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> The Netherlands Backs EU Decision on Balkan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Netherlands' Deputy Foreign
Minister Birkan Benschop said here Wednesday that his country
supported the decision by the European Union (EU) leaders to base
its agency for the reconstruction of the Balkans in the northern
Greek city of Thessaloniki.
</P>
<P>
Benschop made the remarks after talks here with his Greek
counterpart, Yiannos Kranidiotis.
</P>
<P>
The EU decision for Thessaloniki as the seat for the Balkans
reconstruction service must be implemented, he said, adding that
the port of Thessaloniki was not only a port of hope, but a port
of reconstruction for the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
Thessaloniki, the largest city in northern Greece, was chosen
as the headquarters for the EU's agency for the reconstruction of
the Balkans when EU leaders met later June in Rio de Janeiro on
the sidelines of an EU summit with Latin American countries, but
some EU members are now trying to move the agency to Pristina,
capital of the Yugoslav province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Benschop said that Dutch companies were interested in forming
joint ventures with Greek companies on projects involved in
reconstructing the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
Dutch companies could provide know-how and telecoms and
construction experience, he added.
</P>
<P>
Benschop welcomed the resumption of negotiations between Greece
and Turkey, saying that this would contribute to improved dialogue
between the EU and Turkey. 
</P>
