<HEADLINE> UAE, Venezuela Reiterate Need to Observe Oil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates (UAE)
and Venezuela Wednesday reiterated the need for all members of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) to abide by
their production quotas to protect oil prices.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also reiterated the need for continuous
cooperation between OPEC members and non-OPEC countries to ensure
better oil prices, the official WAM news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that UAE Minister of Petroleum and Mineral
Resources Obeid Bin Saif Al Nasir had met with a senior
Venezuelan delegation here.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, comprising senior officials from the Venezuelan
Foreign Ministry and Ministry of Energy and Mines, arrived here on
Tuesday as part of the tour of OPEC member countries to drum up
support for Venezuela's efforts to host an OPEC summit next
February.
</P>
<P>
During their meeting, the two sides also expressed their
satisfaction with the improving oil prices, which had hit 18
U.S. dollars per barrel, the highest in 18 months.
</P>
<P>
Alfaro Silva, director general of the Venezuelan energy and
mineral resources, denied the claim that his country was reneguing
on its quota to flood the oil market.
</P>
<P>
When asked about his country's choice on the contest for the
seat of the OPEC secretary-general between Saudi Arabia and Iran,
Silva said his country was still studying the issue.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the delegation delivered a message from Venezuelan
President Hugo Chavez to UAE President Sheikh Zayed Bin Sultan Al
Nahyan, inviting him attend the possible OPEC summit next year,
WAM said.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also promised to open embassies in each
other's capitals to further develop relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
