<DOCNO> XIE19990715.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Tariff Reduction Scheme to Start in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The phased reduction of
tariffs between southern African countries would start on January
1 next year, a meeting in Gaborone, Botswana, of 12 southern
African trade ministers agreed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
South African Press Association (SAPA) quoted Tanzanian Trade
Minister Iddi Simba, who chaired the meeting, as saying that by
the end of the year these governments would ratify the Southern
African Development Community (SADC) protocol which provides for
free trade throughout the region within five years.
</P>
<P>
He said this would clear the way for tariffs on the majority of
goods traded between member states to be abolished by January 1,
2000.
</P>
<P>
"There is no disagreement over the ratification of the treaty,"
 Simba said. All countries who signed the protocol when it
originated in August 1996 were committed to ratification.
</P>
<P>
The ministers had given their officials a mandate to resolve
problems over rules of origin, a point which had snagged earlier
negotiations, by August 27.
</P>
<P>
"There is nothing left to form a bone of contention between us
to prevent ratification. The rules are being clarified and we
have given a mandate to our officials to work them out. They have
a deadline and we will meet again in South Africa on August 27,"
Simba was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Of the 14 SADC member states, only the Democratic Republic of
Congo (DRC) and Seychelles were not represented at the Gaborone
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Opening the meeting, Botswana Commerce Minister George Kgoroba
said the implementation of the trade protocol was the greatest
challenge facing the SADC.
</P>
<P>
"It will tell potential investors that SADC is ready for them,"
he said. "It is the way to achieve full regional integration in
the shortest possible time."
</P>
<P>
SADC Deputy Executive Secretary Prega Ramsamy said
implementation of the protocol would show how ready the SADC was
to become a serious player in the international economic arena.
</P>
<P>
The governments of Botswana, Tanzania, Zimbabwe, Namibia and
Mauritius have already ratified the protocol. Two thirds of the
original 11 signatories have to ratify the document before the
SADC secretariat can start the process of implementation.
</P>
<P>
Three phases of tariff reduction are planned. All or the
majority of items in group A, which accounts for 60 percent of
traded goods, will kick in with a zero tariff rating on January 1.
</P>
<P>
Tariffs on group B items will be liberalized gradually over the
five remaining years of the eight-year period. Group C is for
"sensitive" items.
</P>
<P>
SADC negotiator Chungu Mwila said that broadly defined, the A
group was everything except textiles, clothing, assembled motor
vehicles, leather goods and some agricultural products. He
foresaw last-minute special arrangements for sugar and beef, and
the fishing industry.
</P>
<P>
Simba said he was confident any remaining problems over such
items would be resolved before the August meeting, but in any
event would not delay the ratification of the protocol.
</P>
<P>
The 14 SADC members are: Angola, Botswana, DRC, Lesotho,
Malawi, Mauritius, Mozambique, Namibia, Seychelles, South Africa,
Swaziland, Tanzania, Zambia and Zimbabwe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990715.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian University Official Suspended over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government Wednesday
announced the suspension of the vice chancellor of the Obafemi
Awolowo University in Osun State following the killing of five
students last Saturday in cult related violence.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian Ministry of Education said in a statement issued here
that the decision was made because of "recent events in the
institution" which fixed Thursday and Friday as days of "mourning
in memory of students killed during the mayhem."
</P>
<P>
The suspension decision came a day after students of the
institution stormed a police station in Oshogbo, capital of Osun
State and forcefully took away suspect Idahosa Efosa they had
handed over for interrogation.
</P>
<P>
Efosa was handed over to the police after at least five
students of the institution, including the general secretary of
students association, were shot dead in cult related violence.
</P>
<P>
Yinka Johnson, a student leader, announced Wednesday the arrest
of five persons in connection with that incident, adding that
"three of them have confessed to participating in the shooting"
and that Vice Chancellor Wale Omole had been declared "wanted by
the students".
</P>
<P>
The vice chancellor of the institution, one of the country's
premier universities, had been criticized for "treating cult
members in the institution with kid gloves."
</P>
<P>
The student leader said investigations by the students showed
Saturday's killings were perpetrated by "a collection of cultists
from the eastern and western zones of the country".
</P>
<P>
The students said they decided to take the law into their hands
after an incident in March this year when the police released five
cult members handed over by the students.
</P>
<P>
Cult membership recently became a problem in tertiary
institutions in the west African country after inter-cult clashes
left hundreds of fellow students dead across the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
