<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Countries Fail to Finalize Free Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Southern African trade
ministers Wednesday failed to finalize a free trade agreement for
the region at a meeting in Gaborone, Agence France Presse (AFP)
quoted Tanzanian Trade and Industry Minister Iddi Simba as saying.
</P>
<P>
But Simba, who chairs the ministerial committee of the Southern
African Development Community (SADC), held out hope that the
phased reduction of trade tariffs between countries in the region
would still begin by January next year.
</P>
<P>
He said officials from SADC's 14 member states would meet in
South Africa on August 27 to put the finishing touches to the
agreement before a SADC summit in Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
The agreement is to clear the way for the abolition of tariffs
on at least 60 percent of goods traded between member states from
January 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
"The protocol will be on schedule," Simba said at a news
conference in Gaborone. "We are going to work very hard to make
sure that it will begin in January."
</P>
<P>
"The meeting in South Africa is where the ministers are
expected to agree on the outstanding issues," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Simba said negotiations faltered on two cornerstones of the
agreement -- the tariff reduction schedule and the rule of the
origin of goods.
</P>
<P>
Members of the Southern African Customs Union -- South Africa,
Namibia, Botswana, Lesotho, and Swaziland -- were happy with the
proposed eight-year reduction schedule, while less industrialized
non-members wanted the process to be stretched out over 10 to 15
years.
</P>
<P>
South African Trade and Industry Minister Alec Erwin said
progress has nonetheless been made on the two outstanding issues.
</P>
<P>
"We have been waiting to get a clearer indication on the rules
of origin and tariff reduction before we could ratify the
protocol. We are now going to present a bill calling for the
ratification of the SADC protocol before the next parliamentary
session," he said.
</P>
<P>
Simba said Lesotho, Malawi, Mozambique, Swaziland and Zambia
indicated that they too were prepared to ratify the agreement
before the end of the year -- paving the way for implementation.
</P>
<P>
He said member states, notably South Africa and Zimbabwe, will
in the meanwhile continue bilateral talks on tariff reductions.
</P>
<P>
Erwin and his Zimbabwean counterpart Nathan Shamuyarira are to
meet in Bulowayo, southern Zimbabwe, Thursday to discuss improved
access for Zimbabwean goods to the South African market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
