<HEADLINE> IFC Launches South African Rand Global Notes Offering </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The International Finance
Corporation (IFC) announced Wednesday that it has launched a South
African rand 100 million borrowing (approximately 16.3 million
U.S. dollars) under its Global Medium Term Note program.
</P>
<P>
The 5-year notes carry a coupon of 13.75 percent and an issue
price of 101.025 percent. The proceeds of the issue were swapped
into U.S. dollar floating rate funds. The lead manager was Toronto
Dominion Securities, London.
</P>
<P>
This transaction on July 12, 1999 represents the third
borrowing for IFC's fiscal year 2000, which started at July 1, and
brings IFC's market borrowings for the current fiscal year to
about 266 million dollars. The funds which IFC raises in the
international capital markets are used to support the operations
of IFC, including its lending operations.
</P>
<P>
The mission of IFC, a member of the World Bank Group, is to
promote private sector investment in developing countries, which
will reduce poverty and improve people's lives. 
</P>
