<HEADLINE> Greece, Slovenia Sign Military Cooperation Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Greece and Slovenia signed here
Thursday a military cooperation agreement which provides for joint
exercises, officer training and information exchange.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, which will be finalized in the Autumn at a
meeting of military experts of the two countries, was signed by
Greek Defense Minister Akis Tsohatzopoulos and his Slovenian
counterpart, Franci Demsar, who is in Greece for an official visit.
</P>
<P>
Before the signing of the agreement, the two ministers
discussed the Kosovo problem, Slovenia's prospects of joining NATO
and the European Union (EU) and bilateral defense cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after their talks, Tsohatzopoulos reiterated that
Greece was opposed to solving the Kosovo crises by military means.
He stressed the need for security policies which should be based
on the fundamental principle of respecting existing borders.
</P>
<P>
Security in the Balkan region must be viewed as a whole and
this required the support of the international community, the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Demsar will visit the multinational training center
and the 181 Hawk guided missile squadron in northern Greek city of
Thessaloniki. 
</P>
