<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Dispels Rumors On Troop Withdrawal From </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwe National Army Thursday
 dispelled rumors that the withdrawal of its troops from the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) was expected to start nest
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman of the army Chancellor Diye said that the withdrawal
was, as indicated by Defense Minister Moven Mahachi Monday,
expected to start within next three to four months.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwe News Agency quoted the spokesman as saying that
the troops would only be withdrawn after the United Nations had
deployed its peace- keeping forces in the vast central African
country.
</P>
<P>
"The withdrawal will depend on the situation on the ground,"
said Diye. " Once the rebels sign the cease-fire agreement and
once it holds and when the United Nations peace-keeping force has
taken over from us, then the withdrawal will start."
</P>
<P>
"It will also depend on whether there are signs that the
cease-fire is working or not. According to our timetable in the
cease-fire agreement, it will start in about four months," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Contrary to recent reports, Zimbabwe would not contribute any
troops to the U.N. peace-keeping force.
</P>
<P>
Recent press reports said Zimbabwe would contribute about 2,000
soldiers for peace-keeping efforts.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, together with Namibia, Angola and Chad, deployed
troops to the DRC when the Tutsi-led rebels allegedly backed by
Uganda and Rwanda launched an attack on DRC President Laurent
Kabila's forces in early August last year.
</P>
<P>
The peace accord was signed by the Southern African Development
 Community leaders, plus the leaders of Rwanda and Uganda in
Zambian capital Lusaka last week.
</P>
<P>
However, DRC rebels, due to their clashes within, refused to
sign the cease-fire agreement.
</P>
<P>
The peace accord is aimed at re-establishing Kinshasa's control
over the whole of the third largest African country and merge
three main separate rebel forces with the government army.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
