<HEADLINE> Eritrea Accepts OAU Peace Formula </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Eritrea has formally accepted
proposals put forward by the Organization of African Unity (OAU)
to end its border war with Ethiopia, according to a new release
from the Eritrean Foreign Ministry available here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
At the closing of the 35th OAU summit in Algiers Wednesday,
Eritrean President Isaias Afewerki announced Eritrea's official
acceptance of the Modalities for the Implementation of the OAU
Framework, according to the news release.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the agreement was done "in the interests of
peace, which we owe not only to the people of Eritrea but also to
the people of Ethiopia, and our continent as a whole," said the
Eritrean president.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Eritrean Foreign Ministry accused Ethiopia of being
ambiguous over the agreement while "indulging in strident and
invective language against Eritrea".
</P>
<P>
The new revised framework agreement calls for armies from both
sides to withdraw from position held before May 6 last year when
the two nations went to war over a disputed part of their common
border.
</P>
<P>
It is not settled whether a peace-keeping force will monitor
the withdrawals, but the next step is for independent arbiters to
judge which land belongs to whom.
</P>
<P>
Despite the mediation made by the international community,
there is no immediate end visible to the conflict. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990715.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Urges International Community to Exert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides
Thursday stressed that a shift in Turkey's position on Cyprus
would come about if the U.N. Security Council, the G-8, Europe
and others exert their influence on Turkey.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks after a commemoration service for those who
died in July 1974.
</P>
<P>
On July 15, 1974, the Greek junta, then ruling Greece,
orchestrated a coup against Cyprus president Archbishop
Makarios. Five days later, Turkish troops invaded and occupied the
northern third of the island.
</P>
<P>
Since then Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish
Cypriots-controlled north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south.
</P>
<P>
"Turkey's long standing goal has been to secure sovereignty,
decisions by consensus, equal representation, rotating presidency
and a separate state," Clerides said.
</P>
<P>
All these, he added, are elements that make up a confederation
and "they were rejected and are rejected now as well."
</P>
<P>
Any change in Turkey's position would depend to a great extent
on whether the international community exerts its influence in
the same direction, Clerides said.
</P>
<P>
"A Cyprus settlement must be found in the framework of
U.N. Security Council resolutions," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-led international community has been trying for
decades to reunite the Cyprus island through a bi-zonal,
bi-communal federation formula, but so far no tangible results
have been achieved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990715.0071 </DOCNO>
