<HEADLINE> Egypt, Tanzania Hold Summit Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
held talks on Thursday with visiting Tanzanian President Benjamin
Mkapa on issues in Africa and ways of enhancing bilateral ties,
said an Egyptian official.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Information Safwat el-Sherif told reporters after
the meeting that the two leaders discussed the resolutions and
recommendations reached during this week's 35th summit of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) in Algiers, Algeria.
</P>
<P>
Their talks covered ways to seek "peaceful solutions to the
conflicts in Africa," said the minister.
</P>
<P>
They also discussed Mubarak's call for an international
anti-terrorism summit under the sponsorship of the United Nations
Security Council.
</P>
<P>
African leaders on Wednesday unanimously adopted a plan to
bring an end to the bloody 14-month border war between Eritrea and
Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
The three-day OAU summit also adopted a convention on
preventing and combating terrorism, calling on member states to
sign it and the U.N. to convene an international conference.
</P>
<P>
The summit also agreed to ban governments that take power by
force from attending future gatherings until they accept
democratic reforms.
</P>
<P>
The talks further dwelt on means of fostering bilateral
cooperation in economy, agriculture, trade and construction, and
exchanging expertises in other domains, el-Sherif said.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa, who arrived here earlier on Thursday for a three-day
official visit, also met with Egyptian businessmen and urged them
to do business in Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak visited Tanzania in 1984. 
</P>
