<HEADLINE> China Making LNG Imports Part Of Its Planning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 15 (Xinhua)-- China will make liquefied natural
gas (LNG) facilities part of its unified planning, according to
Zhang Guobao, the Deputy Secretary General of the State
Development Planning Commission (SDPC).
</P>
<P>
Detailed feasibility studies have to be conducted to avoid any
hasty decision, he says, but a proposal is for first-phase
construction of a 3-million-ton/year LNG receiving terminal at
Chentoujiao in the southern city of Shenzhen that is expected to
be completed by 2005, Zhang said at a two-day seminar.
</P>
<P>
There will also be a natural gas grid extending about 267
kilometers and two new gas-fueled power plants.
</P>
<P>
In addition, three power plants using oil as fuel at present
will switch to natural gas and LNG will be piped to Shenzhen,
Dongguan, Guangzhou, and Foshan and supplied to Hong Kong for
power and urban use.
</P>
<P>
During the second-phase of the project, which is scheduled for
operation in 2009, capacity of the terminal will be expanded to
five million tons of LNG a year and the city gas grid will be
further extended by 240 kilometers Zhuhai and other cities.
</P>
</TEXT>
