<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WFP Launches New Program for Ultra-poor Women in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The World Food Program (WFP)
officially launched a new 18-month cycle of the Vulnerable Groups
Development (VGD) program here Thursday to help the ultra-poor
women in Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
The program will help the poor women to come out of extreme
poverty, State Minister for Women and Children Affairs Zinnatun
Nessa Talukder said at the inaugural function, which was attended
by Dr. Werner Kiene, the country representative of the WFP,
officials from government agencies, non-governmental
organizations, donors and ex-VGD beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
Emphasizing the important role played by the VGD program in
helping the poor women to come out of extreme poverty, she said
the government has taken various steps to make the program more
development-oriented.
</P>
<P>
The new cycle, which started on July 1, 1999, will provide food
assistance to about 500,000 ultra-poor women all over the country.
This is the largest poverty alleviation program assisted by the
WFP across the world, a press release said.
</P>
<P>
Kiene explained the new concept of food assistance as a tool
for "enabling development" emerging in the worldwide context.
</P>
<P>
The 30 million ultra-poor people in Bangladesh, who consume
less than 1,800 kilo-calorie a day, are not yet part of the
mainstream development process, he pointed out. They deserve
support for them and for their children, he added.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the role of food assistance, Kiene said food
assistance through the VGD program enables the poor women to
graduate to a level from where they can look for other development
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
The VGD program provides food assistance of 30 kilograms of
wheat to poor women over a period of 18 months. The beneficiaries
also receive training in income-generating activities,
awareness-raising on legal rights, health and nutrition issues and
credit. After the 18-month food support period, then women become
members of NGOs, thereby able to further improve their
socio-economic condition in a suitable way.
</P>
<P>
The program, which started in 1975 as a relief intervention,
has shifted its focus over the years from relief to development,
having covering about 8,336,000 poor women worldwide since its
inception in 1974. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990715.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier's Prescription For Economic Ills (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Premier Zhu Rongji gave his
prescriptions for the country's weak consumer demand, declining
exports and foreign investment, slow increase in fixed-asset
investments, and dropping consumer prices to cabinet members and
provincial governors here today.
</P>
<P>
 This included increased investment in infrustructure,
technology and education, revamping state-owned enterprises (SEO),
and allowing foreign investment in more industries.
</P>
<P>
 Zhu said that the economic situation has been positive and
encouraging thanks to the "active" financial policy of late last
year. The GDP for the first half of 1999 grew 7.6 percent over
the same period of last year, summer harvests were satisfactory,
industrial production was on the rise, and SEOs saw growth in
profits.
</P>
<P>
 However, because of the changing international and domestic
situation in March and April, certain problems in the Chinese
economy have surfaced and insufficient market demand is especially
noticeable, he said, pointing to 5 aspects of work that need to be
considered for economic development this year:
</P>
<P>
 -- More government funds need to go to infrastructure,
technical innovations at SEOs, and especially to the inerior of
China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990715.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier's Prescription(2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
 -- Consumer spending should be increased by increasing
incomes of urban and rural people, with special attention being
paid to the large number of medium and low-income people and the
large rural population. Policies on increasing consumer loans must
be formulated as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
 -- Exports should be increased by taking steps to attract
more foreign investment and to use it effectively. Foreign
investment should be allowed in a wider range of fields and
policies that adversely affect foreign investment should be
adjusted and services for foreign-funded enterprises in China
should be significantly improved.
</P>
<P>
 -- Reforms of SEOs are to be carried out according to recent
instructions from President Jiang Zemin. The process of
modernizing their management must be sped up and burdens on
enterprises need to be eased to reach the goal of revamping large
and medium-sized SEOs by the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
-- The 9-year compulsory education system must be
implemented and high-school, vocational, and higher education need
to be encouraged to make education a lucrative business, to
stimulate the growth of related fields, and to benefit society in
the long run.
</P>
<P>
 Zhu told those gathered that they should have a clear idea
about the current economic situation, and recommit themselves to
combating problems. He said he himself is confident about the
prospect.
</P>
<P>
Vice-President Hu Jintao presided over today's meeting,
which was also attended by vice-premier Li Lanqing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
