<DOCNO> XIE19990715.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Negotiations for Releasing Greek Bus Hostages Continue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Greek police Thursday continued
their negotiations with a grenade-armed Albanian for the release
of seven hostages in a bus hijacked by the Albanian Wednesday
afternoon in Polykastro near Thessaloniki in northern Greece.
</P>
<P>
Greek police Wednesday night blocked the bus outside Florina,
a some half-hour drive from the border with neighboring Albania,
and a senior police official said Thursday that the Albanian,
identified as Aleksandr Nana, would not be allowed to leave with
the seven hostages, six passengers and the bus driver, the
semi-official Athens News Agency (ANA) reported.
</P>
<P>
This is the second similar incident in northern Greece in less
than two months. On May 29, an Albanian armed with an assault
rifle and a hand grenade hijacked a Greek bus with passengers on
board near Thessaloniki. After being paid ransom of 50 million
drachmas (about 158,730 U.S. dollars), the 24-year-old Albanian
forced the driver to cross over into Albania where he and a Greek
hostage were shot to death by Albanian police.
</P>
<P>
The crisis came at an exceptionally sensitive moment in
Greek-Albanian relations, amidst Greece's efforts to round up and
deport illegal immigrants and consequent protests by Albania over
charges of Greek police brutality against Albanian nationals.
</P>
<P>
Greece's Interior Minister Vasso Papandreou, who is chairing a
crisis management committee comprised of herself and the press,
defense and public order ministers, said that negotiations between
the Greek police and the Albanian hijacker were continuing with
patience, persistence and calm. But, she said, the man continued
to insist on his initial demand of a ransom of 250 million
drachmas (about 793,650 dollars) and safe passage to Albania with
all his hostages.
</P>
<P>
The Greek police are now trying hard to resolve the problem
within Greek territory.
</P>
<P>
A team of psychologists, accompanied by senior police officers,
have been choppered into the area, which has already been closed
off by special police forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
