<HEADLINE> Yeltsin's Aide Denies Having Swiss Bank Accounts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Top Kremlin aide Pavel Borodin
denied on Thursday media reports that he or his wife has accounts
in Swiss banks.
</P>
<P>
"Neither I nor my wife have anything to do with Swiss bank
accounts. I have not engaged in commercial or any other activities
in Switzerland," the Interfax news agency quoted Borodin as saying.
</P>
<P>
The denial came after reports that prosecutors in Geneva,
Switzerland, announced Wednesday that they have opened a criminal
money-laundering investigation into Borodin, his wife and 22
others, many of them purportedly highly placed Russian state
officials.
</P>
<P>
The prosecutors said the investigation, opened by the Geneva
General Prosecutor Bernard Bertossa, would link Russian officials
to money laundering in Swiss banks.
</P>
<P>
No charges have yet been filed, but Bertossa's staff is
checking into whether the 24 people had Geneva bank accounts and
how they used them.
</P>
<P>
"We have reason to suspect it was bribe money being laundered,
" The Moscow Times newspaper quoted investigating magistrate
Daniel Deveau as saying.
</P>
<P>
Borodin said his department, which oversees the renovation of
the Kremlin, was audited by a team of 122 inspectors in 1998.
</P>
<P>
"They found nothing criminal in my work or the operation of my
department," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I have said many times that all these media attacks on me
have been made at clearly political orders," Borodin said. "One
can invent anything."
</P>
<P>
He said he did not receive any official notification from
Swiss prosecutors about the opening of a case.
</P>
<P>
"I want to say once again that this dirty campaign has evident
political undertones," Borodin said.
</P>
<P>
In March, Russian prosecutors entered the Kremlin to seize
documents from Borodin's office related to renovation work by
Mabetex, a Swiss-based construction firm.
</P>
<P>
Mabetex is run by an expatriate Kosovar Albanian, Bahgjet
Pacolli, and has won lucrative construction projects across the
former Soviet Union -- from renovating the Kremlin to rebuilding
both the TsUM department store in central Moscow and the
international air terminal in Kazakhstan's new capital of Astana,
The Moscow Times said.
</P>
<P>
In April, Borodin's apartment was searched, according to a
report at the time by Komsomolskaya Pravda, which said the search
turned up documents of about 100 million U.S. dollars in various
wire transfers to personal accounts in Switzerland, Liechtenstein
and the Bahamas. Borodin later denied those allegations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
