<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Nuclear Scientist Details Visits to Chinese, U.S. Weapon Labs (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The "Cox Report" alleged that Chinese Research Institute of
Engineering Physics (CRIEP) had intended to acquire intelligence
by utilizing the chances of lab-to-lab interactions with the U.S.
</P>
<P>
"After getting approval from the Chinese government and the
American government in 1994, CRIEP and three American national
laboratories including Los Alomos Laboratory started cooperation
and exchanges," said CRIEP president Zhu Zuliang at a press
conference held here today by the Information Office of the State
Council.
</P>
<P>
"Such cooperation and exchanges are completely conducted
within the framework approved by the two countries," Zhu said. "
The issues concerned in these cooperation and exchanges are arms
control and environmental protection. And in terms of arms control,
it includes the nuclear nonproliferation."
</P>
<P>
Zhu has been engaged in manufacturing nuclear weapons for
decades, who has participated in organizing and leading the
development of China's nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
"All the Chinese and American scientists and officials
participating in such cooperation and exchanges know where their
national interests and national security lie, and the
responsibility they assumed for it," he said, adding that it was
impossible for anyone to touch upon nuclear weapon secret
information.
</P>
<P>
"The fields involved are determined beforehand," Zhu said.
Whether it was a visit to the US laboratory or to the Chinese
laboratory, it was in the unsecured areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
