<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopian Refugees in Kenya Fly Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. High Commissioner for
Refugees (UNHCR) Thursday started the repatriation operations of
more than 1,400 Ethiopian refugees from the Dadaab camps in
northeastern Kenya to Gode and JIjiga, Ethiopia's Ogaden Region.
</P>
<P>
The operation kicked off Thursday morning as the
UNHCR-chartered aircraft landed in Dadaab and 53 refugees boarded
the plane for a two-hour flight to Gode, said the UNHCR branch
office in Kenyan capital Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
Each of the returnees received a reintegration package and food
aid plus the equivalent of 60 U.S. dollars to assist them to
reach their home areas and to get reestablished, the office said.
</P>
<P>
The airlift marks the last large return movement of long-time
Ethiopian refugees from Kenya, which once hosted nearly 100,000
Ethiopians, and some of the returnees have been assisted at the
camps since 1991.
</P>
<P>
The agency expects the airlift operations to continue for the
next several weeks.
</P>
<P>
Yvette Stevens, UNHCR representative to Kenya and Somalia, said
her agency only hoped that conflicts in the Horn of Africa could
be resolved so that "we do not see any further refugees from a
region that so much deserves the benefits of peace."
</P>
<P>
There are some 180,000 refugees in Kenya, down from 420,000 in
1992 following repatriation operations mainly to Ethiopia and
Somalia, according to UNHCR branch office here. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
