<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Nuclear Scientist Details Visits to Chinese, U.S. Weapon Labs (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"There are strict secret protection in the arms laboratories of
both countries," Zhu said. "It is impossible for one side to steal
the nuclear secrets of the other. Dr John C. Browne, head of the
Los Alamos National Laboratory, has made this point clear in his
testifying to the Congress."
</P>
<P>
"As to the exchanges of visit of personnel, it involves the
major leaders of laboratories of the two countries," he said. Such
visits and cooperation are beneficial to both sides. For instance,
Integrated Demonstration of Material Protection, Control and
Accountability was jointly held by the two countries last year in
Beijing, which showed the continuous bilateral cooperation on
nuclear nonproliferation.
</P>
<P>
"Cox Report" says that through their visits to American
laboratories, Chinese scientists tried to get more information to
improve China's fluid mechanic device.
</P>
<P>
"In fact, the Chinese delegation never made access to any such
device during their visits to the three American national
laboratories," Zhu said. "On the contrary, when leaders of
American national laboratories visited China, they went to the
place where we put our fluid mechanic device."
</P>
<P>
"If the bilateral exchanges, particularly China's visits to the
American laboratories, are called stealing nuclear secrets," Zhu
said, "I'd like to ask President Clinton to explain how he defines
the American's visit to Chinese weapon laboratories."
</P>
</TEXT>
