<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Consumer Price Index Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's Consumer Price
Index (CPI) for June this year rose by 2.1 percent to 118.8 points
from 116.3 points in June last year, the Statistics Department
announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The index, however, decreased by 0.1 percent when compared with
118.9 points in May this year.
</P>
<P>
The CPI rose 3.3 percent to 118.6 points in January-June this
year from 114.8 points in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The department attributed the 3.3 percent increase in the index
in January-June this year to increases in the indices of seven
main groups such as food, beverages and tobacco, medical care and
health expenses, recreation, entertainment and cultural services.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, the index for clothing and footwear fell 1.9
percent to 97.7 points while that for transport and communication
was flat at 103.9 points.
</P>
<P>
The department said the two main groups of food and gross rent
and fuel and power together accounted for 75.6 percent of the
overall increase recorded in the current period.
</P>
<P>
The department also said the 0.1 percent decrease in June over
May CPI was brought about by falls in three main groups, namely,
miscellaneous goods and services, food and recreation,
entertainment, education and cultural services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
