<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Hopes to Inject Vigor to Export Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Commerce and Finance
Minister Ishaq Dar said Thursday fiscal relief, non tax measures
and abolition of anomalies under the new trade policy will help
foster export growth, halving trade deficit to 800 million U.S.
dollars during 1999-2000.
</P>
<P>
Exports and imports targets for the new fiscal beginning from
July 1 have been set at 9 billion dollars and 9.8 billion dollars,
according to the new trade policy announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The targets are "realistic under the prevailing economic
atmosphere," Dar told a press conference here.
</P>
<P>
During fiscal 1998-99, Pakistan registered a trade deficit of
1.56 billion dollars as exports totaled 7.72 billion dollars while
imports amounting to 9.28 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dar said the trade policy for 1999-2000 has been carefully
conceived keeping two major aspects in view.
</P>
<P>
First, the policy should facilitate the strategy for export-led
growth by increasing export earnings, reducing the trade deficit
and supporting the balance of payments.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, he said, as Pakistan enters a new millennium of
globalization, with competition intensifying for market share, "we
need also to prepare ourselves for the challenges and obligations
of various WTO agreements."
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the new exports target was "most likely"
to be achieved in view of unit value picking up and world trade
recording enhanced activity.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that various incentives and concessions granted under
the policy fabric will help unleash conducive and hospitable
milieu and explore non-conventional avenues to propel exports
pace.
</P>
<P>
The new policy provides income tax relief to increase exports
of engineering, contracting and consultancy services, exports of
branded rice, fish and other food items as well as gem stone
exports.
</P>
<P>
Besides income tax relief, the exports are also entitled to
many other duty concessions.
</P>
<P>
Dar also explained changes in the import policy to promote
exports and national production.
</P>
<P>
These include a sales tax exemption on the import of new or
used machinery and equipment for the domestic housing and
construction industry as well as the import of bulldozers and
angle dozers without payment of customs duty and sales tax.
</P>
<P>
Dar also told journalists that Special Commercial Courts at
Lahore and Karachi are being immediately set up to expedite
resolution of trade disputes and complaints. 
</P>
</TEXT>
