realistic" decision in rejecting the bill, which was approved by
the parliament last Thursday and had prompted concerns from
neighboring Russia and international organizations for its
perceived discrimination against minority rights.
</P>
<P>
It mandates the use of the Latvian language at most public
functions and in business, even those involving only Russian
speakers, who account for 40 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
"Now, the matter rests with the Latvian parliament. Latvian
lawmakers should heed the opinion of the international community
and make the necessary amendments to the draft law in order to
ensure legitimate rights of ethnic minorities who make up almost
half of the population of Latvia," the Russian Foreign Ministry
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Russia's lower house of parliament, the State Duma, also
welcomed the Latvian president's decision.
</P>
<P>
Latvian President Vike-Freiberga explained her decision in a
special television program, Tass reported.
</P>
<P>
"If we took the road to Europe, we should prove our ability to
harmonize our laws with European norms," the president said.
</P>
<P>
She said shortcomings in the bill were made due to haste
rather than as "an unfriendly gesture with respect to other
countries."
</P>
<P>
The same mistake should not be repeated in the future and it
is necessary to hold thorough consultations with international
experts and local specialists, Vike-Freiberga said. 
</P>
