<HEADLINE> U.N. Team Starts Destroying Chemical Agents in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 15 (Xinhua) -- A U.N. technical team, which is
entrusted to remove toxic chemical agents left behind by U.N. arms
inspectors, started its work on Thursday, said a U.N. official.
</P>
<P>
Prakash Shah, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan's representative
in Baghdad, told reporters that the U.N. team started on Thursday
to destroy the chemical agents and mustard gas samples left behind
by the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) on disarming Iraq in its
Baghdad laboratory.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. team, led by South Africa's chemical production
technologist Dirk van Niekerk, comprises four chemical experts
from the Organization for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons
(OPCW) in the Hague and an independent biological weapons expert.
</P>
<P>
These U.N. experts are from China, Russia, Poland and
Germany. Yako Yalato, a Finnish, former Assistant Director of
U.N. Baghdad Monitoring and Verification Center (BMVC), acts as
guide for the U.N. technical team which arrived in Baghdad on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Iraq and the U.N. reached an agreement last month on the
composition of the technical team to close UNSCOM's Baghdad
laboratory where one kilogram of mustard gas and VX gas were left
behind by UNSCOM before it withdrew from Iraq last December.
</P>
<P>
UNSCOM suspended its work of weapons inspections in Iraq last
December when the United States and Britain launched four-night
airstrikes against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, the Iraqi News Agency reported
earlier Thursday that Iraqi technical experts led by Presidential
Adviser Amer al-Saadi and the U.N. technical team held talks at
BMVC on how and where to destroy these mustard gas and chemical
agents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
