<DOCNO> XIE19990715.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Restructures Tax Offices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 15 (Xinhua) -- China is reshuffling its one-
million-strong tax offices personnel through re-organization,
evaluation, and ideological education in order to make them meet
the demand of the market economy and enhance the use of taxes as
an economic lever.
</P>
<P>
Jin Renqing, commissioner of the State Administration of
Taxation (SAT), said the tax system still has "many problems"
despite major restructuring over the past five years.
</P>
<P>
The problems include overlapping organizations, insufficient
management, inadequate supervision, overhead, and not qualified
personnel.
</P>
<P>
Jin noted that some tax offices have employed so many temporary
workers to levy taxes that their inexperience has damaged the
image of the government.
</P>
<P>
He said that the tax system will continue to restructure its
organizations and make clear their specific functions this year,
adding that the number of employees at province-level tax offices
will be slashed and redundant staff will be relocated to lower
level offices. He said that the one million employees of tax
offices around the country will undergo strict evaluations of
their professional proficiency and those who fail the evaluation
will be laid off and re-trained.
</P>
<P>
For example, the Municipal Bureau of National Tax in the city
of Yichang in central China's Hubei Province has laid off and
retrained 95 people over the past six months.
</P>
<P>
China's tax revenue has been growing at a double-digit rate for
the past few years, and the government is paying increasing
attention to taxes as a major lever for the economy.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the country's tax revenue increased by 100 billion
yuan over 1997, account for the total value of additional treasury
bonds issued for the year. This revenue played a key role in the
government's policy of stimulating economic growth to offset the
impact of the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Premier Zhu Rongji praised the tax system for its efforts to
strengthen administration, close tax loopholes, punish corruption,
and collect overdue taxes.
</P>
<P>
Jin said that the tax system will continue to fight against
corruption.
</P>
<P>
For example, Liang Huaquan, the former head of the National
Taxation Bureau of Jixian county in north China's Hebei Province,
was arrested on Tuesday for involvement in the largest corruption
scandal in the history of New China's tax system. He is charged
with allowing personnel in the tax bureau to divert and embezzle
more than 20 million yuan of tax money in 1997 and 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990715.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNDP Report Says Globalization Should Help People, Not Profits (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The 1999 Human Development Report
of the United Nations Development Program (UNDP), says that
globalization is more than the flow of money and goods and
involves the growing interdependence of the world's people.
</P>
<P>
This offers great opportunities for enriching people's lives
and creating a global community with shared values, it says, but
markets have been allowed to dominate the process and benefits
have not been shared equally.
</P>
<P>
Since 1990, the UNDP has asked an independent team of experts
every year to report on major issues of global concern and to look
beyond per capita income as a measure of human progress to such
factors as life expectancy, literacy, and overall well-being,
because human development is ultimately a process of increasing
choices in people's lives.
</P>
<P>
This year's report focuses on the positive and negative aspects
of globalization, which is defined not only in economic and
financial terms, but also in terms of technology, culture and
government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990715.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNDP Report Says Globalization Should Help People, Not Profits (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
What is happening is a grotesque and dangerous polarization of
people and countries who benefit from the system and those who
receive its effects, the report says, and globalization, as it has
been allowed to go so far, has driven a deeper wedge between the
richer and many poor countries and between people inside countries.
</P>
<P>
It says that the income gap between the richest fifth of the
world's people and the poorest fifth, measured by average national
per capita income, increased from 30-to-1 in 1960 to 74-to-1 in
1997.
</P>
<P>
The inequality of globalization driven by profits is wider and
deeper and touches all aspects of human life, it says. Moreover,
care, which is at the heart of human development, is threatened
today because competitive markets put pressure on time, resources,
and incentives for caring, without which individuals and social
cohesion do not flourish.
</P>
<P>
The global markets grow far faster than measures that govern
them and there are repercussions for people, it says, while
efforts to increase global governance are focus almost entirely on
economic aspects, and human concerns are largely neglected, so all
countries need to guard against its risks and human costs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990715.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNDP Report Says Globalization Should Help People, Not Profit (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
However, globalization is controllable and changeable, the
report says, and with a commitment by the global community, the
marginalization, human insecurity, and inequality can be overcome
and this can bring far better results in human development.
</P>
<P>
In China, it says, the country's Foreign Direct Investment (FDI)
was worth 45.3 billion U.S. dollars in 1997, ranking number one
among the top five recipients of FDI of developing countries, and
China's Human Development Index (HDI) ranks 98 out of 174 this
year. Its HDI was at 106 last year.
</P>
<P>
It is a measure of a country's achievements in life expectancy,
education, and adjusted real income. The method of determining HDI
has changed so that no immediate and direct comparison can be made
of each country with previous years, the report says.
</P>
<P>
Kerstin Leitner, the resident representative of the UNDP and U.
N. Resident Coordinator in China, said at a release ceremony for
the report that it will serve as an important reference tool for
China's policy makers, scholars, and external development partners.
</P>
<P>
She said she hopes that the report will enliven the debate
about globalization and ensure that it has more of a human face in
the future.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
