<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Indonesia Enters New Period of Change, Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The successful general election in
Indonesia held on June 7, during which the opposition Indonesian
Democratic Party of Struggle (PDI-P) obtained a relative majority
vote by beating the three-decade dominant Golkar Party, signals
the world's largest archipelago country is entering a new period
of change and development.
</P>
<P>
According to final election results announced by the General
Election Committee (PPI) Thursday, PDI-P has won 33.73 percent of
the votes, becoming the largest political force in the country.
The ruling Golkar Party, which had won past six elections with
more than 70 percent of the votes in each election, is second with
22.44 percent of the votes.
</P>
<P>
As many as 48 political parties contended for 462 seats of the
500-member House of Representatives (DPR) in the election, the
first multi-party election in 30 years. The remaining 38 seats are
reserved for the military, whose members do not vote.
</P>
<P>
Political analysts here said that the results in favor of the
PDI-P reflected the real aspiration of most Indonesians who have
been thirsting for democratic politics and economy in the country.
</P>
<P>
The PDI-P led by Megawati Soekarno Putri, which broke away from
the original Indonesian Democratic Party (PDI) last October, put
up such a good performance in a short time because of its
long-time fight against the New Order regime marked by autocracy
and corruption headed by former president Soeharto who stepped
down in May last year amid the country's worst political and
economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
The "anti-status-quo" program put forward by the PDI-P and
other reformist parties in their election campaign won strong
support from different sectors of the society, especially in big
and middle-sized cities in Java, where 60 percent of the total
population live.
</P>
<P>
The previously suppressed reform forces are becoming
increasingly stronger, although the oppressive forces still
persist in maintaining the status quo, observers said.
</P>
<P>
Political experts said the PDI-P could be in lead over the
other 47 parties in the election also because the party has
released a series of policies tallying with the present national
situation. It was repeatedly stated that the party will work to
reinstate the authority of law, carry out the investigation into
the wealth of former president Soeharto and his cronies, and press
ahead with the fight against corruption. The party also held that
the removal of the military's social and political functions
should be done gradually.
</P>
<P>
In the economic field, the PDI-P and some other reform parties
are determined to speed up the economic recovery by stabilizing
the rupiah's exchange rate, reducing the interest rates and
reforming the unhealthy economic structure, especially the
banking system.
</P>
<P>
Following the outbreak of the region's monetary turmoil in
mid-1997, Indonesia became the worst hit, with the rupiah losing
over 70 percent of its value against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
In a situation where the demand for reform is riding high and
the people are paying high credit to the reform forces, the
winning factions including the PDI-P are facing a very good
opportunity to build a new Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
However, analysts said, they are facing serious challenges of
delivering the many promises they made during the election
campaign. Firstly, the reform forces should make a strong
coalition in the parliament against the Golkar because no party
won a single majority in the election. But it is not easy since
there are different opinions among the parties. Secondly, a clean
and effective government free from corruption, collusion and
nepotism should be established. Thirdly, proper economic policies
should be drawn up to pull the country out of the prolonged
economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Political observers and foreign diplomats here said the most
important thing before the future government is to create the
national conciliation in the whole country where riots and
violence have been taking place since May last year. "Without
focusing on this, every effort to empower the people will fail,
because many things could still not be overcome, such as the
environment problem and the people's fear due to the security
situation," an observer noted.
</P>
<P>
"We want to see how the (new) government would raise our status
as a nation facing the challenges of the 21st century," a
legislator said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
