<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Trying to Reduce Dependence on Rubber Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government is trying
to reduce dependence on rubber imports by making best use of
locally-produced rubber resources, Environment and Forest Minister
Syeda Sajeda Chowdhury said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The minister made the remarks while inaugurating a refurbished
display and sales center of the Bangladesh Forest Industries
Development Corporation (BFIDC).
</P>
<P>
He said the government is trying to further develop 15 rubber
plantations to discourage imports.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh's rubber farming has a bright prospect since the
climate, chemical components of soil and yearly rate of rainfall
in the northern, northwestern, northeastern and southeastern parts
of the country are favorable for rubber cultivation, experts said.
</P>
<P>
Rubber plantation was first started in Bangladesh in 1955 on an
experimental basis, and a comprehensive program was undertaken in
1975 in the country to attain self-sufficiency in rubber.
</P>
<P>
The present demand for raw rubber in the country is about
30,000 tons a year, and its demand is expected to reach 41,000
tons by the year 2000 and 70,000 tons by 2010.
</P>
<P>
Some 4,108 hectares of land has been brought under rubber
plantation since 1987 in the northwestern districts of Tangail and
Rangpur, and another 20,000 hectares of land can be brought under
rubber plantation in the country.
</P>
<P>
The BFIDC can now produce only 3,200 tons of rubber per annum.
As per volume of plantation and age of trees, the yearly
production would be increased to 10,000 tons, BFIDC officials
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
