<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Official Says Cox Report Won't Affect China's Space Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 15 (Xinhua) -- China's aerospace industry won't
be affected by the "Cox Report" released earlier this year by the
Select Committee of the U.S. House of Representatives, which
accuses China of stealing America's "sensitive technology",
according to Zhang Lihui, director of the Research and Development
Department of China Aerospace Science and Technology Corporation.
</P>
<P>
China's Long March Carrier Rockets have had 15 successful
launches from October 1996 to June of this year, and the report
can't slow down China's space industry, Zhang said at a State
Council Information Office press conference.
</P>
<P>
The report has, however, jeopardized credibility of China's
space industry and Sino-U.S.trade, Zhang said. But it has also
hardened the determination of Chinese aerospace scientists and
technicians and their confidence in developing China's aerospace
industry independently.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that using Chinese rockets to carry American-made
satellites is making use of space science and technology in a
peaceful way for the welfare of mankind, but that the report has
seriously jeopardized and even stopped this healthy cooperation
and that many Sino-U.S. satellite contracts are on hold.
</P>
<P>
China's space industry has widespread international cooperation
all over Europe, Asia, and Africa and, as far as Zhang knows,
China has very active commercial cooperation with these areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
