<HEADLINE> Thailand Develops Infrastructure to Boost Border Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government plans to spend
three billion baht (81 million U.S. dollars) on developing
infrastructure to boost trade with neighboring countries, a report
of Thailand News Agency said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The budget will be spent on the continuing construction of
roads linking border areas and provinces, as well as
telecommunication and electricity system, which have been
suspended due to financial crunch during the country's economic
crisis, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The investment plan was inspired by official statistics showing
a significant increase in the country's border trade over the
first four months of this year, which reached 225.8 billion baht
(6.1 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
A study released by the National Economic and Social
Development Board (NESDB) showed that border areas between
Thailand and Myanmar should be developed and promoted for trade
and tourism while those between Thailand and Laos should be
developed for agricultural production and processing, which could
be linked to southern China and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
The NESDB study also said that the Thai-Cambodian border should
be developed as a center for investment while the Thai-Malaysian
border should be promoted for trade and tourism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
