<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand PM Opens Chinese Splendor Exhibition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAMILTON, New Zealand, July 15 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Prime
Minister Jenny Shipley cut the ribbon for Chinese Splendor
Exhibition and officially declared the exhibition open Thursday in
Hamilton, a big city on New Zealand's North Island.
</P>
<P>
The 90 relics on display are selected from 120,000 pieces
housed in the Shanghai Museum. They include ancient bronze
vessels, jade, lacquer ware, porcelain and paintings. The oldest
exhibit is 5,000 years old.
</P>
<P>
Shipley spent more than one hour, watching all the exhibits
with great interest.
</P>
<P>
She told Xinhua that she loves these relics. "They are so old,
but have been preserved so well," she said.
</P>
<P>
"We are indeed lucky to live in an age where the glories of
ancient cultures can be moved around the world and enjoyed by so
many people," she noted.
</P>
<P>
"I am looking forward to visiting China next week, as part of
New Zealand's year as Chair of APEC. Viewing this exhibition will
prepare me well for that," Shipley added.
</P>
<P>
She said that during her China trip, she will exchange views
with Chinese leaders on priorities her country has set for the
forthcoming APEC Leaders' Informal Meeting. She will also discuss
with them ways to expand New Zealand-China bilateral relationship,
especially in trade and tourism.
</P>
<P>
"New Zealand and China are very good friends. Our two countries
have a long history of warm relations," she said.
</P>
<P>
Present at the opening ceremony were Hamilton Mayor Russ
Rimmington, Chinese Consul-General to Auckland Wu Zhuqiu, and over
300 New Zealanders and local overseas Chinese.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition at the Waikato Museum of Art and History will
last 12 weeks. Museum Director Jenny Cave told Xinhua that her
museum is honored to display priceless Chinese relics. She
believed the exhibition will serve as a bridge between cultures of
New Zealand and China.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese relics were on show in Dunedin, an important city
on New Zealand's South Island, earlier this year, and attracted
thousands of local people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
