<DOCNO> XIE19990715.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 11:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian President in Cairo for Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President Benjamin William
Mkapa arrived in Cairo Thursday for a four-day official visit at
the invitation of Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak led senior Egyptian officials to greet Mkapa at Cairo
International Airport and the two leaders later held a tete-a-tete
session of talks, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Mkapa will discuss with Mubarak ways of
promoting the bilateral relations, and regional and international
issues of common interest, Tanzanian Ambassador in Cairo Muhamed
Mwinyi Mzale told the news agency Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Mzale said that Mkapa's visit "falls within the context of
distinguished and special friendship" binding the two countries'
presidents.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa's visit is aimed at fostering the bilateral relations in
all domains, especially in the economic and trade areas, the
Tanzanian ambassador said.
</P>
<P>
Mzale underlined that the visit will provide "a good
opportunity" to the two leaders to take up issues related to the
bilateral ties, foremost of which is to activate the
Tanzanian-Egyptian Joint Committee formed in 1986.
</P>
<P>
He asserted that the two countries enjoy historical cooperation
relations and share views vis-a-vis regional and international
issues.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa will reiterate support for Mubarak's efforts to bring
peace to the Middle East and Africa, Mzale said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, the first Arab country to sign peace treaty with Israel,
has played a key role in mediating the Arab-Israeli peace talks
since the peace process kicked off in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Cairo is also keen on seeking solutions to raging conflicts on
the African continent, including the civil war in the Democratic
Republic of Congo, Eritrean-Ethiopian border disputes and the
civil war in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Mkapa is expected to meet with Egyptian
businessmen in a bid to encourage them to invest in Tanzania and
promote bilateral trade, the Tanzanian ambassador said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
