<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Slightly Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
closed firmer Thursday, with investors nervous about the release
of inflation figures in the United States, brokers said.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index recovered from negative
territory in late trade to close 10.6 points higher at 3,065.0,
seven points below the intra-day peak.
</P>
<P>
"The market was a bit all over the place, there was no clear
direction," Reynolds &AMP; Co. adviser Markus Mueller said.
</P>
<P>
"There are some fairly important figures coming out of the
United States tonight, so ahead of that, the market was probably
going a bit cautious," he noted.
</P>
<P>
On the Australian bourse, the all industrials index added 14.3
points to 5,301.0 and the all resources index rallied 9.3 points
to 1,314.6 points.
</P>
<P>
Among bank stocks, ANZ was the best performer, surging 35.3
cents, or 3.18 percent, to 11.456 Australian dollars amid the talk
that it has dropped its opposition to mergers between the "Big 4"
players.
</P>
<P>
The National Australia Bank climbed 10.9 cents to 24.15
Australian dollars and Westpac firmed 3.3 cents to 9.88 Australian
dollars, while Commonwealth Bank retreated 8.7 cents to 24.12
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Overall, the bank index shot 46.4 points higher to 6,486.6
points.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 438.01 million stocks worth 1.28 billion
Australian dollars (845 million U.S. dollars). Rising stocks
outnumbered falling stocks 616 to 575 and 438 stocks were steady.
</P>
</TEXT>
