<HEADLINE> China's Guangdong Reports Drop in Foreign Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Guangdong, the leading foreign
trade province in China, saw a drop in both imports and exports in
the first six months this year.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, the province did 60.53 billion U.S.
dollars worth of foreign trade from January to June, down 3.1
percent from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The province exported 32.26 billion U.S. dollars worth of
commodities, down by 12.2 percent or 4.48 billion U.S. dollars,
and imported 28.27 billion U.S. dollars worth of commodities, up
ten percent.
</P>
<P>
Some 38.3 percent of China's foreign trade is conducted by
companies in this south China province.
</P>
<P>
China had a decline of 4.6 percent in exports in the first half
of the year, but exports showed some signs of recovery during the
period, according to the latest Customs figures.
</P>
<P>
Statistics released by the General Administration of Customs
show that China's exports reached 83 billion U.S. dollars between
January and June while imports during the period surged 16.6
percent to 75 billion U.S. dollars, bringing the total trade
volume to 158 billion US dollars, up 4.4 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
