<HEADLINE> EU Donates Angola $3M Medicine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) has donated
medicine worth 3.36 million U.S. dollars to the Angolan
government.
</P>
<P>
EU representative to Luanda, Antonio Cardoso Mota said that the
batch of 1,850 kits of medicine include anti-paludics, antibiotics
and analgesics, which could serve 50 health institutions.
</P>
<P>
The Journal of Angola newspaper Thursday quoted the envoy as
saying that the donation was part of the post-war emergency aid
program.
</P>
<P>
The 15.75-million-dollar cooperation program between the EU and
the Angolan government in health began in 1995 to help the
southern African country facing serious shortage of medical
services.
</P>
<P>
Angolan Minister of Health Adelino Manassas was quoted as
saying that the EU donation came just in time.
</P>
<P>
The minister noted that the humanitarian situation has
deteriorated in his country after the civil war renewed last
December, saying that some 1.7 million people are suffering from
the shortages of food and medicine. 
</P>
