<HEADLINE> Shanghai Stock Exchange Resumes Issuing New B-Shares </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The Shanghai Stock Exchange, one
of China's two stock markets, today resumed issuing new B-shares,
the stocks available to overseas investors, after a hiatus of
nearly six months.
</P>
<P>
The Dongbei Electrical Appliances Co. Ltd. based in Huangshi
City in central China's Hubei Province, one of the country's
leading refrigerator compressor producers, became the first new
company to begin issuing B-shares on the exchange in nearly half a
year.
</P>
<P>
The company scheduled an issue of 115 million B-shares on the
Shanghai exchange, 100 million of which were already sold out in
late June, according to an exchange source.
</P>
<P>
The issuing of the Dongbei B-shares brings the total number of
B-shares on the Shanghai stock market to 54.
</P>
<P>
China's B-share market has suffered from a capital shortage and
sustained stagnation since its debut, and declined to its lowest
point last year as a result of the Asian financial crisis and a
lack of confidence among overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
Beginning on May 19, however, the Chinese stock market started
to enjoy a bullish run, which led to a strong rebound in B-share
prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
