<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tourists to Zanzibar Double in 4 Years: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The improvement of
infrastructure facilities and promotional campaigns abroad have
given a strong push to the development of tourism in Zanzibar
isles.
</P>
<P>
Tourist arrivals in Zanzibar, which lies off the east coast of
the mainland Tanzania, have doubled in four years, from 41,433 in
1994 to 86, 445 in 1998, Zanzibari Minister of Information,
Tourism and Youth, Issa Mohammed, has said.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the House of Representatives in Zanzibar Wednesday,
the minister said that the tourism sector has witnessed an
encouraging trend particularly with regard to the mushrooming of
first-class hotels.
</P>
<P>
Beds at the hotels increased from 4,210 in 1997 to 4,925 in
1998, Tanzania's major newspaper The Daily News Thursday quoted
Mohammed as saying.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the government has taken measures to solve
most of the problems stalling tourism development, such as
improving the transport network and security.
</P>
<P>
Zanzibar's participation in international exhibitions in
Western countries has greatly publicized the islands, hence
attracting more tourists, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, tourist arrivals in 1998/99 fiscal year which
ended in June this year slightly dropped by 13 percent primarily
because of the hike in tourist visa fees from 10 U.S. dollars to
40 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, tourism earnings have slightly increased to
138,698 dollars in 1998/99 from 137,920 dollars realized in the
previous year, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Zanzibar, comprising the twin islands of Unguja and Pemba, as
well as a number of smaller islands, is famous for its beaches and
historic sites.
</P>
<P>
The Zanzibari government has attached great importance to the
development of tourism, after its major income earner, the exports
of cloves, declined sharply due to fall of the prices of the cash
crop in the international market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990715.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 12:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek, Turkish Cypriots to Negotiate Without </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of Defense William
Cohen said here on Thursday that Greek and Turkish Cypriots must
resume talks with no preconditions.
</P>
<P>
At a joint press conference with his Turkish counterpart
Sabahattin Cakmakoglu, Cohen said that the U.S. supports the call
for the solution to the Cyprus issue through direct dialog.
</P>
<P>
Cohen arrived in Ankara Wednesday evening on a one-day visit to
Turkey, part of his six-leg tour which also includes stops in
Greece, Norway, Denmark, Hungary and Albania.
</P>
<P>
He said that "the U.S. supports the call from NATO (North
Atlantic Treaty Organization) General Secretary Javier Solana,
U.N. Security Council and important countries for this direct
dialog," adding that "Washington wants a federation of two
communities and two regions. This is our position."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriots-dominated
south and the Turkish Cypriots-controlled north since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
In 1983, Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf denktash declared the
breakaway "Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus," which is now
recognized only by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying for decades to reunite the island
through a bi-communal federation formula, but the talks between
the two sides have made no substantive progress.
</P>
<P>
In his part, Cakmakoglu said that "we state that it is easy for
the Turkish and Greek Cypriot sides to solve the Cyprus issue
under the foundation of equality."
</P>
<P>
"Third party's interference will make the Cyprus issue more
complicated," added the Turkish minister.
</P>
<P>
In a unanimously approved resolution on June 29, the
U.N. Security Council urged U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan to
invite the Turkish and Greek Cypriot sides to resume talks.
</P>
<P>
According to the resolution, the talks should start with no
preconditions, all aspects of the conflict be on the table and the
negotiations last until a settlement is reached.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. resolution followed a similar appeal by the G-8,
grouping the U.S., Canada, Britain, France, Italy, Germany, Japan
and Russia.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of the G-8 urged Annan "to invite the leaders of
the two parties on Cyprus to negotiations in the fall of 1999."
</P>
</TEXT>
