<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Begin Research in Arctic Ice-Floe Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SNOW DRAGON, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese expedition ship
Snow Dragon with more than 120 scientists and journalists aboard
reached 70 degrees north latitude in the Arctic floating-ice
region today.
</P>
<P>
Floating ice can be seen all around the expedition ship, which
stopped in the Chukchi Sea.
</P>
<P>
Much of the research covering oceanic geology, chemistry, and
biology has already begun, according to Qin Weijia, assistant to
the chief scientist of the expedition.
</P>
<P>
A China-produced helicopter had its first test flight over the
Arctic Ocean today.
</P>
<P>
The team members of the expedition are divided into three
groups encompassing the atmosphere, sea ice, and the ocean. The
present good weather is most favorable to the studies, according
to Qin.
</P>
<P>
During their two week voyage since leaving Shanghai at the
beginning of this month, scientists have collected aerosol and
carbon dioxide samples, and oceanic temperature observations and
fishery resources exploration have also been conducted.
</P>
<P>
The expedition ship is scheduled to stop more than 20 times for
various scientific studies in the Chukchi Sea in the next ten days,
before heading further north to a latitude of 80 degrees.
</P>
<P>
Following that, some team members will be transported by
helicopter to an ice region further north, according to chief
expedition scientist Chen Liqi.
</P>
<P>
This is Chinese scientists' first expedition to the North Pole,
where they will study the effect of the North Pole on the global
climate, especially on China, the ecological system in Arctic
waters, and the atmosphere, geology, fishing, and marine
environment of the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
