<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 51,000 Afghans Return Home From Pakistan in Half Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 15 (Xinhua) -- At least 51,000 Afghan refugees
have returned home from Pakistan in the past six months, reports
here said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Niaz Ahmed, spokesman for the United Nations High Commission
for Refugees (UNHCR) based in Peshawar, capital of Pakistan's
North West Frontier Province, was quoted as saying that they
assisted 51,000 Afghans from January to June this year.
</P>
<P>
The UNHCR is providing every registered returning Afghan
refugee family with three bags of wheat and 5,000 Pakistani
rupees.
</P>
<P>
The organization assisted 80,000 people last year to return to
Afghanistan by providing them cash, wheat and tarpaulins.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed said that they are assisting those who really want to
return home and will continue to do so in future.
</P>
<P>
Once those refugees reach Afghanistan, there are other agencies
inside the country to help them, he said.
</P>
<P>
Afghan refugees are estimated at about 2.6 million -- 1.4
million in Pakistan and 1.2 million in Iran. 
</P>
</TEXT>
