<HEADLINE> Ulster Unionist Party Absent from N. Irish Assembly Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The key Ulster Unionist Party (UUP)
on Thursday did not attend the session of the Northern Ireland
Assembly scheduled to set up a new power-sharing executive for the
British province.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Thursday, Protestant leader David Trimble said his
Ulster Unionist Party would not nominate ministers at the session.
</P>
<P>
Trimble made the announcement to a news conference in Belfast
15 minutes before the assembly of Catholics and Protestants was to
convene, dashing hopes of a last-minute solution to a crisis over
IRA disarmament, that has brought the Good Friday peace agreement
to a halt.
</P>
<P>
The assembly started shortly after Trimble's announcement
without any of the 28 UUP members present, according to a Reuters
report filed from Belfast.
</P>
<P>
Trimble said his UUP planned to set up a "shadow administration
" and urged British authorities to revoke the session as soon as
possible so that the peace process could be "parked" and discussed
further.
</P>
<P>
Thursday was the deadline set by British Prime Minister Tony
Blair for the assembly to meet to decide ministerial posts, which
are to be shared among Protestant Unionist and Catholic
Nationalist politicians, according to earlier reports.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue to work constructively with the other parties
to ensure that we achieve the creation of a genuinely democratic
government in Northern Ireland," Trimble was quoted as saying.
</P>
