<DOCNO> XIE19990715.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water Runs High at Middle Reaches of Yangtze River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The second flood crest of the
Yangtze River, China's longest, has haunted this central Chinese
city for more than four days, with the average water level being
monitored at 27.7 meters.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, the second flood peak reached Wuhan,
capital of central China's Hubei Province, in the early morning of
July 11, and since then the water level has been running above 27.
7 meters. At 8 am today, the water level was monitored at 27.80
meters, and showed no sign of receding.
</P>
<P>
Wang Jun, a water control expert from the Yangtze River Water
Conservancy Committee, blamed the continuing high water level on
the constant rain in the valley of the upper reaches of the
Yangtze and the ongoing water surge from upstream.
</P>
<P>
Though the water level in the main stream of the Yangtze is
running high, the pressure on the fortified embankments along both
banks of the river in Wuhan is not too great at present.
</P>
<P>
The Yangtze divides Wuhan into three parts: Hankou, the
business district, Hanyang, a comparatively poor district, and
Wuchang, the district of universities and government organizations.
</P>
<P>
As the second flood peak has been passing, the water level has
been at about four meters above the ground in the urban areas of
Wuhan. Nevertheless, local residents are remaining calm in the
face of the rising water levels.
</P>
<P>
Flooding caused by heavy rainfall along the Yangtze River
Valley since late June has killed more than 200 people and
threatened the lives of 60 million local people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
