<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Metro Manila Gets Intelligent Traffic Lights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- In a bid to ease the worsening
traffic condition of the capital region, the Philippine government
has installed "intelligent" traffic lights in 90 out of the 444
intersections in Metro Manila.
</P>
<P>
Godofredo Galano, director of the Traffic Engineering Center,
said Thursday that these Sydney Coordinated Adaptive Traffic
System (SCATS) signals are in addition to the 50 "signaled"
intersections already existing in the region.
</P>
<P>
These "intelligent" traffic lights are controlled by
underground sensors that can detect which lane is jammed with
vehicles and then activate the green light for that lane much
longer, Galano said.
</P>
<P>
Galano noted that Metro Manila's present traffic control
system, which was started in 1978, has already surpassed its
threshold of efficiency.
</P>
<P>
"Its fixed time system, which is based on 1981 traffic data,
can no longer cope with or respond accurately and instantly to
present situations," he said.
</P>
<P>
SCATS, whose software is owned by the government of New South
Wales in Australia, is described by its sellers as a sophisticated
system that could reduce stops by at least 40 percent, cut travel
time by 20 percent, and fuel consumption by 12 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990715.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
