<DOCNO> XIE19990715.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal Formulates IT Development Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The Nepalese government has
formulated a three-way plan to develop information technology to
match the growth in the world, a National Planning Commission
(NPC) official said.
</P>
<P>
NPC member Shankar Sharma told Xinhua in a recent interview
that the plan includes software development, human resources
development and the establishment of an information technology
park.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that there are about 10 software developing
centers in Nepal but software export is very low.
</P>
<P>
"We have expected that Nepal can export about 60 billion rupees
(882 million U.S. dollars) of software per year within 20 years,
so we're making plans accordingly and working to achieve the
goal," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We can do that if we develop qualified manpower in this age of
global village," he added with confidence.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Sharma said that under the government's plan, two types of
manpower -- software developer and software operator -- will be
developed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a first sum of 10 million rupees (147,058 dollars)
has been allocated for the establishment of an information
technology park in Kathmandu, he said, adding that the park is
expected to be completed in two years.
</P>
<P>
Under the Foreign Direct Investment Act, both private and
foreign investors are encouraged to be involved in the development
of information technology in Nepal, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that thanks to foreign aid, his country is much
computerized, but computers have not been used properly.
</P>
<P>
Now there are only three Internet service providers in the
Himalayan kingdom with some 15,000 Internet users, and in terms of
electronic commerce, only a small project is being run by the
Federation of Nepalese Chambers of Commerce and Industry and the
Ministry of Commerce, he said.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the government is planning to introduce computers in
the government-run schools to expand their use, he said. Private
schools have computer courses.
</P>
<P>
"From the next educational calendar, we will start computer
courses in some government schools and establish computer training
centers specially for school teachers and other government and
semi-government officials from the next fiscal year (starting in
mid-July)," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We also encourage the use of the Intranet among school
teachers and students. This will be started in universities," he
added.
</P>
<P>
"There is a plan of establishing telecenters in all the five
development regions immediately with a view to providing
interconnection facilities to government offices and
organizations," he disclosed.
</P>
<P>
On the constraints Nepal is facing in developing information
technology, Dr. Sharma said that the regulations will be amended
and a cyber law will be formulated to address problems like
unavailability of loans, letter of credit and foreign exchange to
companies in this sector.
</P>
<P>
A high-level committee will be formed soon under the
chairmanship of the NPC vice chairman to clear the way for better
development of information technology in the country, he noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990715.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pressure Mounts on Nigeria's Speaker to Quit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Serious pressure has been mounted on
Nigeria' s Speaker of the House of Representative Alhaji Ibrahim
Buhari to resign in order to save the image of the country's
nascent democracy.
</P>
<P>
The presidency and the Senate have been worried about the
negative reactions from the allegations against the Speaker since
Sunday when the weekly News magazine hit the streets with the
cover story titled "The Face of a Liar..."
</P>
<P>
The News magazine in its current issue alleged that Buhari lied
about his age and claimed educational qualifications he did not
have.
</P>
<P>
The magazine quoted an official of Toronto University of Canada
as saying that at no time did the Speaker attend the university
contrary to his claim.
</P>
<P>
The magazine further alleged that the Speaker is 29 years old
and not 36 as he claimed. The import of this is that he was not
qualified to stand for election into the House of Representatives
as the 1999 Constitution of Nigeria provides that anybody aspiring
to the National Assembly must be at least 30 years.
</P>
<P>
President Olusegun Obasanjo who just returned from Algiers
where he attended the 35th Summit of the Organization of African
Unity (OAU) Wednesday met with five senators from each of all
three political parties on the allegations.
</P>
<P>
Because of the meeting, the Senate could only sit for ten
minutes before it adjourned till Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
The meeting of various party leaders held Wednesday was said to
have resolved that the only way out of the "embarrassing
situation" was for Buhari "to vacate his office".
</P>
<P>
The Senate has set up a 16-man committee in one of its shortest
sittings to investigate the allegations because it considered the
allegations as "a matter of urgent national importance."
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Buhari told the National Assembly that "I wish to
assure you that there is no truth in the story" carried by the
News magazine.
</P>
<P>
He described the allegations of forgery and falsehood levelled
against him as unfounded, adding that the campaign to smear his
reputation is one of the "prices I have to pay for democracy."
</P>
<P>
The Independent Communications Network Limited, publishers of
the News magazine, has challenged the House speaker to go to court
as it refused to apologize as demanded by the speaker's counsel,
Chief Rotimi Williams.
</P>
<P>
The magazine disclosed that it had more than sufficient
evidence to establish that Buhari had no reputation worthy of
protecting by any properly constituted court of law in Nigeria.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990715.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Botha Implicated in Killings: TRC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Former South African
president P. W. Botha has been named by the Truth and
Reconciliation Commission (TRC) as one of those "implicated" in
killings of activists in the apartheid era.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement from the TRC on Thursday, former
apartheid hit squad commander Eugene De Kock and eleven other
apartheid security policemen will appear before the amnesty
committee next Monday for their role in the murder of eight United
Democratic Front youth activists on the East Rand in 1985.
</P>
<P>
According to some of the applicants, the operation was approved
by cabinet ministers, including then state president Botha.
</P>
<P>
TRC spokesman Mbulelo Sompeta said the TRC would convey its
findings to South Africa's prosecuting authorities, which would
decide whether to investigate the findings further and prosecute
anyone.
</P>
<P>
"Implicated persons" were normally notified of their status by
the TRC, Sompeta said, and it was up to them whether they wanted
to attend a hearing or send a lawyer on their behalf.
</P>
<P>
Botha's previous encounter with the TRC ended with him winning
his Cape High Court appeal last month against a conviction for
defying a subpoena to testify before the TRC.
</P>
<P>
The notification to Botha to testify before the commission was
technically invalid, the court said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990715.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. "One China" Stand Noticed, FM Spokeswoman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 15 (Xinhua) -- China has noticed the U.S.
government's position to follow the "one China" policy, Foreign
Ministry spokeswoman said here today.
</P>
<P>
U.S. State Department spokesman James Rubin reaffirmed days ago
that the United States will adhere to "One China" policy.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. government has made a solemn commitment to the
Chinese government on Taiwan issue," Zhang Qiyue said at a routine
press conference this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
During his China visit last year, U.S. President Bill Clinton
publicly reiterated that the United States does not support Taiwan
independence, or "one China, one Taiwan", or "two Chinas", or
Taiwanese membership in international organizations where
statehood is required, Zhang said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
