<HEADLINE> Meeting for Selecting New WTO Director-General Postponed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Representatives from the members of
the World Trade Organization (WTO) postponed a meeting scheduled
for Thursday morning designed for the selection of the new WTO
director-general.
</P>
<P>
No new date was immediately available after the ambassadors of
Bangladesh and Australia called for the delay, the Bangladeshi
envoy Istekhar Chowdhury told reporters.
</P>
<P>
There had been a draft proposal that the two candidates,
Supachai Panitchpakdi of Thailand and Mike Moore of New Zealand,
would serve a three-year term one after another. Both candidates
have indicated they would accept the "3+3" plan.
</P>
<P>
"We thought a postponement would help because this is a subject
of intense consultations and many delegations are seeking
instructions from their governments," said Chowdhury.
</P>
<P>
If the 134 members of the WTO could reach consensus on the
proposal, the first of the two candidates would take up his three-
year post as early as from September 1.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether the United States backed the idea, U.S. Trade
Ambassador Rita Hayes said the plan was "one of many proposals out
there" and the United States would look at it "as it has looked at
all draft proposals." 
</P>
</TEXT>
