<DOCNO> XIE19990715.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Agency Expects Long Spell of Hunger in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Kenya may experience a long spell
of hunger following a decline in maize output in the main rainy
season in 1999, the United States Agency for International
Development has warned in a report.
</P>
<P>
The report, dubbed "Kenya Vulnerability Update", available here
Thursday, said that only 1.83 million tons of maize will be
harvested after poor performance of the long rains from March to
June, about a shortfall of 0.4 million tons.
</P>
<P>
"The output compares unfavorably with the 1991-97 average
long-rains output of 2.16 million tons and to last year's
long-rains output of 2.23 million tons," the report noted.
</P>
<P>
The decline attributes the situation to unusually low and
poorly- distributed rainfall in all parts of the country with the
exception of the areas adjacent to Lake Victoria.
</P>
<P>
Less than normal cumulative rainfall during the 1999 long rains
season had promoted degeneration of vegetation even in the
high-potential districts in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The report added that "the poor vegetative conditions are
expected to continue for next several months in eastern and
northern Kenya since the short rains are not expected until
October."
</P>
<P>
A rapid assessment by Famine Early Warning System and the
Kenyan Ministry of Agriculture in the "bread basket districts" in
Rift Valley Province in central Kenya, revealed unusually poor
conditions.
</P>
<P>
In the five districts in Rift Valley, it is expected that
747,975 tons of maize would be harvested compared to 896,607 tons
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The report said that bean output for the 1999 long rains season
will be 185, 235 tons, representing a 40 percent reduction of the
expected production relative to the 1991-97 average output of
310,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
The worst hit areas, the report pointed out, are the pastoral
districts in North Eastern Province and the absence of rainfall
during June has accelerated the depletion of water, pasture and
browse.
</P>
<P>
The United States Agency for International Development
administers the U. S. foreign assistance program providing
economic and humanitarian assistance in more than 80 countries
worldwide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
