<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HKSAR Signs Air Services Transit Agreement with Kyrgyz </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) signed an Air Services Transit
Agreement with the Kyrgyz Republic Thursday, the third such
agreement signed by the HKSAR since July 1, 1997, following
similar agreements with the Maldives and Lithuania.
</P>
<P>
Stephen Ip, secretary for Economic Services of the HKSAR, and
Alik Askarov, deputy of the Minister of Transport and
Communications and director of the Department of Air Traffic and
Air Space Use of the Kyrgyz Republic, signed the agreement on
behalf of their governments.
</P>
<P>
"The Agreement today marks a new chapter in the development of
the  bilateral civil aviation relations between the HKSAR and the
Kyrgyz
Republic," said Ip at the signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
"I strongly believe that these bilateral relations will
develop in time, and will continue to provide a firm foundation
for the further growth of other economic ties between the two
places," he added.
</P>
<P>
An air services transit agreement facilitates the development
of  international air services by providing a legal framework
which enables
the airlines of both sides to use the most direct and
cost-effective
flight paths which go over the air space of the other side in
operating
international services.
</P>
<P>
Acting under specific authorizations from the Central People's
Government of China, the government of the HKSAR will continue to
negotiate and conclude more agreements with other aviation
partners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
