<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Sees Increasing Older Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Singapore employers have to
rethink their attitudes towards employing older workers in face of
an increasingly aging population, said the Ministry of Manpower in
an occasional paper issued Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Last year, people aged 55 and above accounted for 14 percent,
or about 451,900, of Singapore's resident population, the paper on
"older workers" revealed.
</P>
<P>
The figure will increase to 27 percent or some 1,124,200 by the
year 2000, thus incurring a significant impact on the labor force,
said the paper.
</P>
<P>
"Older workers represent a valuable resource that we can ill
afford to waste," said the paper. "Employers have to rethink their
attitude towards employing older workers and make necessary
adjustments to facilitate their continued employment.
</P>
<P>
It said that Singapore, as other developed countries like Japan
and the United States, has taken such measures as extending
retirement age, reducing the cost of hiring older workers and
re-training and skill-upgrading of older workers.
</P>
<P>
However, it noted that while various measures can contribute to
the continued employment of older workers, their success hinges on
employers changing their attitudes so as not to base employment
decisions on pre-conceived ideas about age.
</P>
<P>
Relative to younger workers, older workers in Singapore are
more vulnerable to job loss and longer unemployment spells, said
the paper.
</P>
<P>
This is because of the higher cost of hiring older workers and
the perception among some employers that they are less productive
and receptive to new ideas, it added.
</P>
<P>
But studies have shown that older workers could perform better
in many jobs, especially those involving service and human contact
such as retail, counseling, social services and consultancy, it
said.
</P>
<P>
They can maintain high levels of performance well into their
50s and 60s in jobs that require much training and experience such
as professional and highly-technical work.
</P>
<P>
"As Singapore moves towards a knowledge-based economy, age may
become less important than skills in sustaining employment," said
the paper.
</P>
<P>
"There is considerable scope for employers to use flexible work
options to allow older persons a more gradual transition from
full-time to retirement enabling them to stay longer in the
workforce," it said.
</P>
<P>
The paper found that among older men in Singapore, only 65
percent were in the labor force last year, compared to at least 80
percent in Japan and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
The same trend holds true for older women in Singapore, of
which 22 percent worked last year, as opposed to 50 percent in
Japan and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
On their education profile, the paper noted that older workers
will increasingly be better educated.
</P>
<P>
By 2010, more than half of them would have at least secondary
education and by 2020 the figure will increase further to
two-thirds, the paper forecast. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
