<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Mining Workers Get 43 PC Salary Hike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's mining industry, which
is under threat from poor international commodity prices and
rising production costs, has agreed to award a 43 percent salary
increase to its workers with effect from this month.
</P>
<P>
The increase was agreed between the Chamber of Mines and
Associated Mineworkers of Zimbabwe, the daily Herald reported on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Chief Executive of the Chamber of Mines David Murangari said
Wednesday that the mining sector has had to bend backwards after
taking into consideration the harsh economic environment, which
has adversely affected both the workers and companies.
</P>
<P>
"The mining industry is also facing a threat in (falling) gold
prices because of the gold sales made by Britain and the proposed
gold sale by the International Monetary Fund (IMF)," he said.
</P>
<P>
Murangari described the gold sales by Britain and the proposed
sale by the IMF as irresponsible, noting that their actions would
worsen the price of gold, which is currently at its 20-year low.
</P>
<P>
About 82,000 jobs could be lost in South Africa and over
100,000 in the sub-Saharan region if gold prices stay below 260
U.S. dollars an ounce.
</P>
<P>
Gold prices declined to around 257 dollars an ounce after
Britain sold 25 tons in an auction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
