<DOCNO> XIE19990715.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Unveils First High-Tech Development Guide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The ten industries that are covered by the listed areas include
agriculture, information, environmental protection and
comprehensive use of resources, medicine, energy, communications,
materials, machine building, construction, and light and textile
industry.
</P>
<P>
The guide, published Wednesday, is jointly compiled by the
State Development Planning Commission (SDPC) and the Ministry of
Science and Technology, and will be revised on a yearly basis.
</P>
<P>
A SDPC official said that with the guide the government wants
to encourage the whole nation to contribute to accelerating high-
tech development with possible resources in a bid to promote the
current economic restructuring.
</P>
<P>
All high-tech projects that meet the requirements of the guide
will be supported by the government by means of reducing or
exempting equipment import tariffs, and offering preferential
loans and state investments, the official said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that attention should be paid to avoiding redundant
projects, calling on enterprises, financial institutions and
governments at all levels to choose projects according to their
own conditions.
</P>
<P>
The SDPC is now working with departments concerned on setting
up a high-tech project database to provide consulting services to
local governments and enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The high-tech sector has just begun to develop in China and
lags far behind leading developed countries in the world in terms
of scale, level and competitiveness. Preliminary statistics show
that the added value of the high-tech sector contributes less than
two percent of China's gross domestic product.  
</P>
</TEXT>
