<DOCNO> XIE19990715.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Drug in Uganda Reducing HIV Transmission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- A new study carried out in Uganda
has revealed that Nevirapine drug can reduce HIV transmission from
mother to babies by 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan Health Minister Crispus Kiyonga and top Ugandan and
American medical researchers revealed the findings at a press
conference in Kampala Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The minister said Nevirapine could prevent some 300,000 to
400,000 new born babies annually in developing countries from
beginning life with HIV, the virus causing AIDS.
</P>
<P>
A single oral dose of the drug is given to HIV-infected women
in labor and to their babies at birth. Mothers have to take it in
a single tablet and the babies as a syrup.
</P>
<P>
The study jointly conducted by Ugandan and American researchers
was sponsored by the U.S. National Institute of Health.
</P>
<P>
It has been going on for one and a half years and would
continue for 15 months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
