<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Willing to Cooperate with APEC on Gov't Procurement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, July 15 (Xinhua) -- China is willing to keep close
cooperation with members of the Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation
(APEC) organization and other parts of the world in a bid to
achieve progress in government procurement.
</P>
<P>
China will adopt a positive attitude toward the establishment
of an open, transparent government procurement system that allows
competition in operation, according to a trade official at the
ongoing APEC Workshop on Government Procurement Practices which
opened Wednesday in Kunming, capital of Yunnan Province in
southwest China.
</P>
<P>
China began to adopt on a trial basis internationally-accepted
practice for government procurement in 1995, and the experiment
has spread from the pioneer city of Shanghai to 28 other provinces,
autonomous regions and cities. Now in China procurement for big
projects financed by the World Bank, the Asian Development Bank
and foreign governments is done through international bidding.
</P>
<P>
To legalize it, China's top legislature, the National People's
Congress (NPC), has listed the stipulation of a government
procurement law a top priority, according to Chi Haibin, a NPC
Standing Committee member.
</P>
<P>
Investigations are underway for the promulgation of the law to
promote the country's economic development, said Chi, who is also
a member of the NPC Financial and Economic Committee and the law's
drafting team.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that Chinese government administrative
institutions spend 700 billion yuan (84 billion U.S. dollars) on
procurement every year. The enactment of a procurement law is
expected to save as much as 80 billion yuan (9.64 billion U.S.
dollars) in annual expenditures.
</P>
<P>
The five-day workshop has attracted representatives and experts
from 14 APEC nations, and the participants will discuss the future
development of government procurement and cooperation between APEC
members in this field, as well as the impact of the World Trade
Organization on this matter.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990715.0217 </DOCNO>
