<HEADLINE> Latvian President Returns Controversial Language bill to Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Latvian President Vaira Vike-
Freiberga has returned a controversial language bill to parliament
for revision, the Itar-Tass news agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The bill, approved by the parliament last Thursday, prompted
concern from neighboring Russia and international organizations
for its perceived discrimination against minority rights.
</P>
<P>
It mandates the use of the Latvian language at most public
functions and in business, even those involving only Russian
speakers, who account for 40 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
"If we took the road to Europe, we should prove our ability to
harmonize our laws with European norms," the president said in a
special television program announcing her decision late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"There is no sense in making clothes with drawbacks in the
belief that they will be patched later," Vike-Freiberga said. "It
is better to mend holes right away or to sew something new, and
then appear before the public."
</P>
<P>
However, Vike-Freiberga stressed, "the key aim of the law --
to protect the Latvian language -- remains intact and is not
subject to revision."
</P>
<P>
The same mistake should not be repeated in the future and it
is necessary to hold thorough consultations with international
experts and local specialists, Vike-Freiberga said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990715.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
