<HEADLINE> Kenya Maps out Malaria Control Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Ministry of Health has
developed a national plan on malaria control in the wake of
criticism from the media and parliament, the East African Standard
newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The plan aims at reducing morbidity and mortality from malaria
through flexible and sustainable strategies, director of Medical
Services Julius Meme has said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the ministry is set to terminate the use of
chloroquine as the main drug in combating malaria since it has
been proved to be no longer effective.
</P>
<P>
The Kenya Medical Association was challenged Wednesday to give
a full report over premature discharge of patients at a Kisii
district hospital in Kenya's Southwest Nyanza Province before
President Daniel arap Moi's visit last Monday so as to give a
false impression.
</P>
<P>
In the past four months, 700 Kenyans reportedly died of
malaria, a tropical disease and top killer in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Local officials in Kisii district claimed that the Health
Ministry has banned the media coverage of the state of malaria
spread. 
</P>
</TEXT>
