<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Takes Preventive Measures Against Dengue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- With the dreaded dengue fever
likely to strike at the onset of the rainy season, the Philippine
government has started taking preventive steps to prevent a
possible outbreak of the disease.
</P>
<P>
Alberto Romualdez Jr., secretary of the Department of Health
(DOH), said Thursday morning that his office has mobilized local
governments nationwide to keep tabs on the so-called "dengue hot
spots."
</P>
<P>
"Dengue downed many people last year. This year, we will keep a
close watch over it," Romualdez said in a radio interview.
</P>
<P>
The DOH, he said, is putting on the fast track its system of
drug procurement to make sure hospitals and local government
health centers have the needed medicines to combat dengue.
</P>
<P>
Romualdez said the DOH and local governments would remain on
alert against dengue until November, when the rainy season is
expected to subside.
</P>
<P>
"The dengue season is long, it lasts up to November. We should
stay alert until then to prevent the situation from worsening," he
said.
</P>
<P>
According to Romualdez, the DOH has noted some cases of dengue
in Nueva Ecija Province in the central Philippines, but local
health authorities acted quickly and prevented the disease from
spreading.
</P>
<P>
Romualdez added that the DOH is also on the lookout for other
diseases that usually strike during the rainy season.
</P>
<P>
Such diseases, he said, include upper respiratory tract
infections due to sudden changes in weather conditions. This
disease often kills children below five years old, he said.
</P>
<P>
To combat this, Romualdez said, the DOH is now conducting
health education classes to advise parents on how to prevent their
children from getting infected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
