<DOCNO> XIE19990715.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Posts 509 Million Dollar Trade Surplus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- With increasing exports and still
weak imports, the Philippines registered a trade surplus of 509
million U.S. dollars for the first five months of 1999, an
official report said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to the trade performance report released by the
National Statistics Office, the country's merchandise exports for
the first five months increased by 12.4 percent to 12.946 billion
dollars from 11.516 billion dollars a year ago.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, payments for imports dropped by 5.2 percent
to 12.436 billion dollars from 13.118 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
These made the merchandise trade for the five months of 1999
grew by 3.0 percent to 25.382 billion dollars from 24.634 billion
dollars last year, the report said.
</P>
<P>
For May alone, total merchandise trade reached 5.280 billion
dollars, 4.8 percent higher than the same month of last year. The
trade surplus of the month was 214 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The report said exports for May amounting to 2.747 billion
dollars went up by 13.7 percent from 2.415 billion dollars a year
earlier, while total payment for imports went down by 3.5 percent
to 2.533 billion dollar from 2.624 billion dollars a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
The report also showed that raw materials accounted for the
biggest slice of the country's total imports for the month at 43.6
percent as payment rose by 4.1 percent to 1.104 billion dollars
from 1.061 billion dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, capital goods accounted for 34.8 percent of the
import bill for May 1999 with payments amounting to 882.24 million
dollars, which was 15.5 percent lower than the 1.044 billion
dollars in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
The United States, accounting for 21.3 percent of the aggregate
import bill, remained as the main source of imported goods for the
month, while Japan and South Korea posted at the second and third
place respectively, said the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
