<HEADLINE> Kenyan President Urges Fight Against Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
has urged church leaders to work with his government to combat
corruption, immorality and other social ills in the country.
</P>
<P>
Moi said his government had intensified the fight against graft
and appealed to the clergy to join hands to wipe out the vice, the
mass media reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The president made the remarks Wednesday as he opened a
four-day Unity for Africa Peace and Prayer Conference in Lake
Victoria city of Kisumu, in southwestern Nyanza Province.
</P>
<P>
Moi noted that church had a moral duty to encourage good
lifestyle by creating awareness among the youth on how to guard
against such vices as drug addiction and irresponsible sex
behaviors.
</P>
<P>
On peace and unity in Africa, the president told the
participants that the two were vital ingredients for social and
economic development.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted with dismay that in most parts of the world,
the search for peace had been shadowed by the pursuit of narrow
selfish interests.
</P>
<P>
In Africa in particular, conflicts and wars continued to take
place with increasing frequency, causing immense suffering and
death each year, the president added.
</P>
<P>
Moi said Kenya was fortunate to have been spared from such
turmoil and upheavals that afflict many countries in the
continent.
</P>
<P>
He also praised the conference organizers for initiating
discussions at finding solutions to common problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
