<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Abide by Congo (K) Truce Pact: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe has reiterated that it
would abide by the terms of the cease-fire agreement signed in
Lusaka last week.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean High Commissioner to Zambia Tirivaffi Kangai said
here Wednesday that Zimbabwe, which is one of the major parties
involved in the 11-month conflict in the Democratic Republic of
Congo (DRC), was committed to the agreement by virtue of President
Robert Mugabe appending his signature to the pact.
</P>
<P>
"It is indeed our hope and expectation that all the other
signatories to that agreement will equally, fully respect and
adhere to what they have signed," Kangai was quoted by Thursday's
Zambia Daily Mail newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said hopes of peace in the DRC were high and there would be
great disappointment in the region and beyond, if the cease-fire
agreement was not respected by even a single signatory.
</P>
<P>
Kangai saidZimbabwe together with other Southern African
Development Community (SADC) member states were still deployed
within the DRC. He said the withdrawal of all forces was scheduled
to be completed within 180 days of the signing of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
The Joint Military Commission (JMC) would in full consultation
with the Organization of African Unity (OAU) and the United
Nations, draw up the detailed schedule for definitive withdrawal
of foreign forces from the DRC, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
