<HEADLINE> Chinese Capital Moves to Improve Investment Climate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Vice-mayor of the Chinese capital
Zhang Mao announced here that the city government will take
effective measures in the near future to improve its investment
climate dramatically.
</P>
<P>
Zhang made the statement at a seminar on policies for foreign-
funded enterprises in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The vice-mayor pointed out that Beijing is expected to sponsor
a quarterly conference every year focusing on important issues in
attracting overseas investment, and an evaluation is expected to
be conducted annually of the city's investment climate to provide
reference for government work.
</P>
<P>
The city government will also improve its work transparency by
opening all sorts of channels for foreign-funded ventures to make
comments on its policies, and the system for foreign businesses to
file complaints will also be perfected, according to the official.
</P>
<P>
Zhang also promised in his speech better services, loosened
control on approval of foreign-funded projects, and better liaison
between the city government and overseas-funded businesses.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from more than 360 overseas-funded enterprises
and commercial units attended the seminar, who raised questions
about customs procedures, foreign exchange settlement and export
rebates.
</P>
<P>
During the first five months this year, Beijing approved 251
overseas-funded ventures, involving 648 million US dollars in
contractual investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
