<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 07:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Discovers Powerful Bomb </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Iranian security forces on
Wednesday discovered a powerful bomb on the Mullah Sadra Avenue in
northwestern Tehran and defused it.
</P>
<P>
"The bomb was very powerful and could have inflicted heavy
losses if exploded," an informed source told local daily Tehran
Times published on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The source also said that the security source also discovered a
hideout used by terrorists in Tehran, but gave no details.
</P>
<P>
The discoveries coincided with a massive rally in Tehran
University against unrest caused by student protests to police
crackdown.
</P>
<P>
Over the past week, Iran experienced the worst unrest since the
1979 Islamic revolution as security forces clashed with protesting
students following an unauthorized police crackdown on the Tehran
University dormitory complex on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
The police assault, a response to a student rally protesting
against the approval of new press law and the closure of the
leading moderate daily Salam (Hello), was widely condemned in the
country.
</P>
<P>
However, Iranian leaders blasted "foreign and domestic enemies"
for being behind the unrest and warned the students of the "black
hands of the enemies."
</P>
<P>
The pro-conservative Tehran Times also said that Iran's
Supreme National Security Council confirmed the involvement of
the elements supporting the Iranian outlawed Mujahedin Khalq
Organization (MKO) in the student protests.
</P>
<P>
The MKO, a main political and military group fighting against
former Iranian shah regime, was announced illegal in 1981
following sharp differences with the then Iranian government.
</P>
<P>
The MKO, labeled as "terrorist group" by Tehran, launched
various attacks on Iranian interest inside and outside Iran
during the past decade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990715.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cell Phone Costs to Fall in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Mobile phone costs will eventually
go down by 45 percent as a result of new initiatives by the Telkom
Kenya Limited, which monopolizes the telecommunications market of
this east African country.
</P>
<P>
Managing Director of the company Augustine Cheserem said
Wednesday that Telkom Kenya has set aside 160 million shillings
(about 2.2 million U. S. dollars) to rehabilitate its
telecommunications network.
</P>
<P>
However, Cheserem did not give a time table for the expected
drop, the East African Standard newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Mobile phone services in Uganda and Tanzania are much cheaper
than that in Kenya. A treaty on the East African Community
consisting of the three countries is set to be signed in late
July, which will boost the creation of a regional common market.
</P>
<P>
Telkom Kenya was carved out of the former state-owned Kenya
Posts and Telecommunications Corporation in a privatization move
according to an act of parliament, which gave Telkom a one-year
guaranteed monopoly of Kenyan market before any strong competitors
are allowed in.
</P>
<P>
"Our telecommunications network has suffered a great deal due
to lack of funds and we hope that liberalization of the sector
will enable us to attract capital from the private sector, " said
Cheserem.
</P>
<P>
He said the company has also embarked on realizing the target
of improving service penetration in the rural areas from the
present 0.16 lines per 100 people to one line per 100 people, and
in the urban areas from four lines per 100 people to 20 lines per
100 people by the year 2015.
</P>
<P>
At an estimated average cost of about 2,000 dollars per line,
the total investment in the period will amount to 5.4 billion
dollars, according to the managing director. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
