<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Revenue Collection Falls Short of Target in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government collected
148.37 billion taka (about 3.059 billion U.S. dollars) of revenue
in the just-ended 1998-99 fiscal year, 5.5 percent short of the
original target of 157 billion taka (about 3.237 billion dollars),
The Independent Daily reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The figure represented a rise of 7.5 percent over the
collection of 138.02 billion taka (about 2.846 billion dollars) in
the previous fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Due to shortfall in revenue collection from the very beginning
of the 1998-99 fiscal ending on June 30 this year, the government
revised down the revenue target at 148.50 billion taka (about
3.062 billion dollars) when Finance Minister Shah A.S.M. Kibria
presented the new national budget in parliament in June.
</P>
<P>
The revenue collection at the end of the financial year,
however, fell short by 0.08 percent against the revised revenue
collection target.
</P>
<P>
Finance Ministry sources said the revenue collection shortfall
was resulted from the exemption of customs duty from a major
proportion of the import. The import of food which constituted a
large portion of the country's import was totally exempted from
the duty payment.
</P>
<P>
The revenue collection from the gas sector fell and from the
sale of tobacco declined causing shortfall in the revenue target,
the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The year experienced unprecedented flood and as a result the
tax collection from domestic business declined.
</P>
<P>
Other factors responsible for the revenue shortage included
decline in the country's industrial production, large scale
smuggling of Indian goods, and a declining trend in exports and
imports, the sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
