<HEADLINE> hke071508 -Sri Lankan Rebels Reject Civilian Safety Zone Proposal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan Tamil rebels have
rejected a proposal by the army to establish a civilian safety
zone in the north of the country, Defense Ministry officials said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The army has proposed the setting up of a five-kilometer-long
and one-kilometer-wide civilian safety zone to serve the
humanitarian needs of civilians in uncleared areas in Wanni.
</P>
<P>
The zone is to encompass 500 meters wide of land on either side
of the main highway in the area, the Defense Ministry said in a
press release.
</P>
<P>
The proposal was made with a view to minimizing confrontations
that will cause severe hardship to civilians, it said.
</P>
<P>
However, the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) has
rejected the proposal and instead favored a much smaller zone of
250 meters long and 250 meters wide on either side of the main
highway.
</P>
<P>
The army said it is hardly adequate to ensure the safety of
civilians.
</P>
<P>
The Defense Ministry has called upon the LTTE to reconsider its
position bearing in mind the welfare and well-being of the public.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE has been fighting a 16-year war against the Sri Lankan
government for a separate homeland for minority Tamils in the
north and east of the country. 
</P>
