<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> URGENT: CHINA MASTERS NEUTRON BOMB TECH (more details with quotes) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 15 (Xinhua) -- China has already mastered the
neutron bomb design technology, said Zhao Qizheng, director of the
Information Office of the State Council, at a press conference
held here this morning.
</P>
<P>
As early as in the 1970s and 1980s, China has already in
succession mastered the neutron bomb design technology and the
nuclear weapon miniaturization technology, Zhao said.
</P>
<P>
Zhao said this while refuting the Cox Report by the Select
Committee of the US House of Representatives, alleging that China
"stole" the design information on the US W-70 warhead (enhanced
radiation nuclear warhead, also known as the neutron bomb) from
the Lawrence Livermore Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
"The neutron bomb seems quite mysterious to ordinary people. In
fact, it is a kind of hydrogen (H) bomb," Zhao said, adding that "
Since China has already possessed atom bomb and H-bomb
technologies, it is quite logical and natural for it to master the
neutron bomb technology through its own efforts over a reasonable
short period of time."
</P>
<P>
China has successfully conducted its first atom bomb test on
October 16, 1964. On December 28, 1966 it mastered the principle
of H-bomb technology. And on June 17, 1967 it successfully carried
out its first H-bomb test.
</P>
<P>
Zhao said that in 1964, Chinese scientist Wang Ganchang
initially advanced the concept of laser-based nuclear fusion. Wang,
who was also an academician of the Chinese Academy of Sciences (
CAS), was considered as one of the scientists in the world who
have first independently put forward the concept.
</P>
<P>
China began systematic research on the technology of laser-
based nuclear fusion. In 1973, one-beam laser was used to drive
deuteron ice and a neutron was observed in the experiment. In 1974
a nuclear reaction took place through the use of one-beam laser on
a drive target of deuteron polymer, and a D-D reaction to produce
a neutron was observed.
</P>
<P>
In 1986 China adopted the direct driving method to produce a
neutron from a glass target capsule filled with D-T gas. Between
1990-92, through experimentation, thermonuclear fusion reaction
was achieved through the method of indirect driving, and
thermonuclear neutron was observed.
</P>
<P>
"It was revealed later from U.S. declassified documents that
Chinese and American scientists almost simultaneously advanced a
similar concept in their respective research," Zhao said,
stressing that "This fully indicates that the law governing
science exists objectively, and people from all over the world can
get hold of it sooner or later no matter what method is used."
</P>
<P>
He said Cox and others would not have made such a "silly"
mistake if they had seriously consulted experts. "It only reveals
their lack of general scientific knowledge," he pointed out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990715.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Auto Sales Increase Sharply in 1st Half of This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's automobile market has
shown an marked improvement as sales in the first half of this
year increased 21 percent to 85,000 units, The Nation reported
here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
For June only, the sales totaled more than 19,000 units, or an
82 percent growth over that of the same month last year.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted Ninnart Chaitheeraphinyo, president of the
Automotive Industry Association as saying that the government's
economic stimulus measures, especially interest rate cuts, have
helped changed consumer trends from saving money to buying cars.
</P>
<P>
The ratio of consumers buying cars with cash has dropped to 50
percent from 70 percent while those buying on credit has increased
to 50 percent from 30 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
Before the economic crisis, 70 percent of cars were purchased
by credit with the remaining financed by cash.
</P>
<P>
"The car industry is quite sensitive to economic trends. When
the crisis broke out it was among the first to be hit. So now that
the market is improving, it should be a sign that the Thai economy
is returning to growth," Ninnart said.
</P>
<P>
The average monthly sale of 15,000 units is well above the
12,000- unit level in 1998, but still far from the peak sales
recorded in 1996 which totaled 590,000 units, or an average of
49,000 units per month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
