<HEADLINE> Chilavert Says Copa Stadia Are White Elephants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Paraguayan goalkeeper Jose
Luis Chilavert said on Wednesday that the three stadia rebuilt for
the Copa America, being held in Paraguay, would become white
elephants after the competition finished.
</P>
<P>
"They (the organizers) said the stadia would be there
afterwards for the benefit of Paraguayan football but they will be
white elephants," the goalkeeper told an Argentine television
sports program.
</P>
<P>
"In the football of my country, the odd match between Cerro
Porteno and Olympia brings in some money, but the other matches
are played without anybody watching."
</P>
<P>
"I've always said that the Copa America should not be held in
Paraguay because in my country, there are a lot of poor people who
don't have enough to eat and we can't afford the luxury of
organizing a tournament of this size."
</P>
<P>
Chilavert, the Paraguay World Cup captain and goalkeeper who
also scores goals frequently from free kicks and penalties,
refused to play in the Copa America in protest at the money spent
in hosting the 12-team tournament.
</P>
<P>
Paraguay were knocked out by Uruguay on penalties in the
quarter-finals, when they appeared to sorely miss his charismatic
and inspiring leadership.
</P>
<P>
According to Chilavert, Uruguay was very inferior to Paraguay
and Paraguay got swept out because the team didn't do things well.
</P>
