<DOCNO> XIE19990715.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Mayon Volcano Causes 5 Earthquakes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' Mayon volcano
caused five high-frequency volcanic earthquakes during the past 24
hours, the Philippine Institute of Volcanology and Seismology
(Phivolcs) said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
However, no significant ground movement of deformation was
observed on Wednesday, the Phivolcs said in a report issued here.
</P>
<P>
The Phivolcs also said steam emission was notably weak for the
latest observation period with a small sulfur dioxide value of 590
tons per day which was considerably less than the previous
measurements that ranged from 1,000 to 4,000 tons per day.
</P>
<P>
The aerial survey conducted Wednesday morning made it possible
to observe the crater directly, the Phivolcs said.
</P>
<P>
"The central explosion pit remained bowl-shaped and is littered
with volcanic deposits derived from the June 22 ash explosion and
from loose deposits of the crater," said the report.
</P>
<P>
Despite the volcano's apparent calm, the Phivolcs maintained
that it is too early to state that volcanic activity is on the
wane because no trend can yet be established.
</P>
<P>
On the contrary, the very small steam and sulfur dioxide output
should be considered abnormal for Mayon, which usually emits
voluminous gases from its crater, the Phivolcs noted.
</P>
<P>
The Phivolcs therefore maintains Alert Level 2 over the
volcano, which is about 330 kilometers southeast of Manila.
</P>
<P>
Alert Level 2 means the public should not venture inside the
delineated six-kilometer radius permanent danger zone and the
seven-kilometer safety buffer zone in the southeast sector.
</P>
<P>
Mayon's last major eruption on February 2, 1993 killed 78
people and affected 17,119 people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
