<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas Investments in Agricultural Development Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIHAI, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Overseas investors have shown
growing interest in investing in agricultural development projects
in Beihai, a port city in south China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous
Region.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, the coastal city has drafted and
published a series of preferential policies to encourage investors,
especially overseas ones, to pump up investment into the
agricultural sector.
</P>
<P>
By late June, the city had approved 43 overseas-financed
agricultural projects which require a total investment of 89.12
million U.S. dollars. Overseas investors actually provided 42.92
million U.S. dollars in cash and 3.548 million U.S. dollars worth
of commodities for the development projects.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the city has also used World Bank loans to
finance four other agricultural development projects, of which,
the project for breeding of aquatic products requires 27.73
million U.S. dollars, and the project for growing vegetables need
a total investment of 10 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Beihai sits on a rhinohorn-shape peninsula at the south China
coast in Guangxi. The city has a coastline of 107 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
With a history of 2,000 years, Beihai is a place from which
merchant vessels used to sail west to the Indian Ocean, passing
the Malay Peninsula and up along Myanmar's coast. With Southeast
Asia across the sea and being close to Hong Kong and Macao, Beihai
is a sea exit for inland areas of southwest China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
