<DOCNO> XIE19990715.0301 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Stock Market Expanding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 15 (Xinhua) -- China had 900 companies listed on
the Shanghai and Shenzhen stock exchanges by July 12, which had
issued 278.75 billion shares.
</P>
<P>
Combined stock capitalization of all companies that have stocks
listed on the two bourses was 2.85 trillion yuan, with 910.113
billion yuan of that coming from traded stocks.
</P>
<P>
China set up its first stock exchange in Shanghai in December
1990, with only eight companies listed. Two years later, that
number rose to 100. In the past year or so, 100 more companies
were added to the exchanges in Shanghai and Shenzhen.
</P>
<P>
The companies listed on the two bourses involve almost all
sectors, from automobiles, chemicals, textiles, electronics, and
metals to commerce, real estate, finance, and tourism. The stocks
have helped the money-hungry companies garner funds, improve their
methods of operation and expand their business.
</P>
<P>
Now the stock markets are playing a more important role in the
nation's economic growth and social development.
</P>
<P>
China now has more than 40 million shareholders, an indication
of enthusiastic responses to the ever-expanding stock market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
