<DOCNO> XIE19990715.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lower Water Level at Source of Yellow River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The water level of Ngoring and
Gyaring lakes on the upper reaches of Yellow River, the second
largest in China, dropped by nearly two meters, according to a
recent survey on the river.
</P>
<P>
Yellow River originates in the Kariqu and Yueguzongliequ lakes
which join flow before entering Gyaring and Ngoring lakes, the
fresh water lakes with the highest elevation in China. Then the
river runs down eastward.
</P>
<P>
Gyaring Lake covers an area of 526 square kilometers with an
average depth of nine meters while Ngoring Lake is 617 sq. km. in
area with a depth of 17 meters. They play a vital role in
adjusting the storage and water flow of the Yellow River.
</P>
<P>
The minimum water flow of Ngoring has reduced from 168 cubic
meters in 1989 to none in 1998. Moreover, water flow between the
two lakes dried up this year for the first time in recorded
history, said Quan Xunzhang, head of the survey team.
</P>
<P>
Gengque, magistrate of Madoi County, said that water runs out
of Ngoring Lake at a rate of 2.71 cubic meters per second and its
intake is 0.006 cubic meters per second. Its water level declines
by one centimeter every four to five days. Other lakes at the
source of the Yellow River have also shrunk or salinized.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
