<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Further Refutes Cox Report (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Zhao Qizheng, director of the
Information Office of the State Council, further refuted today the
"Cox Report" by the U.S. Congress with abundant facts.
</P>
<P>
"To clarify the truth and air the facts, the Information Office
of the State Council has conducted further investigations into the
issues raised in the report," Zhao said at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
He clarified matters and rebutted the subreption related to
manufacture of nuclear weapons, commercial satellite launches,
exchanges of science and technology, economic and trade
cooperation, machine tools, and high performance computers.
</P>
<P>
In a statement on the report made at an earlier press
conference held on May 31, Zhao had pointed out that the
concoction of the Cox Report was a farce aimed at fanning anti-
China mood and undermining Sino-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
"Voluminous facts indicate that the conclusions drawn by the
report do not hold water, and even act contrary to the general
knowledge of science and technology in many aspects," he said.
</P>
<P>
Zhao noted that it was totally groundless that the Cox Report
accused China of "stealing" secret information on the most
advanced thermonuclear warheads possessed by the United States.
</P>
<P>
"It is not only a grave calumny on the Chinese people and
Chinese scientists, but also a kind of obvious racial
discrimination," Zhao said.
</P>
<P>
"As a matter of fact, China has mastered in succession the
neutron bomb design technology and the nuclear weapon
miniaturization technology as early as in 1970s and 1980s," he
added.
</P>
</TEXT>
