<HEADLINE> Barak Arrives in Washington on Mideast Peace Mission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- New Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak arrived in Washington on Wednesday night to discuss with
President Bill Clinton issues of the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
During his five-day visit here, Barak will meet Clinton on
Thursday and again next Monday. He will also hold intensive talks
with Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
Clinton attaches great importance to Barak's visit and has said
he looks forward to the visit "eager as a kid with a new toy."
</P>
<P>
Clinton's Middle East strategy is conciliation between Israel
and Arab nations in the west and containment on Iraq and Iran in
the east. But because of former Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu's opposition to the policy of "land for peace", key to
the peace process, Clinton's strategy has suffered setbacks over
past three years. And now he pins hope on Barak who advocates
conciliation with the Arab nations.
</P>
<P>
But Barak would not like the United States "overly involved" in
the Middle East matters. Before his departure for Washington, he
told the New York Times that the Americans should be able to
return to their "special role as facilitators" and stop acting as
"arbitrator, policeman and judge."
</P>
<P>
That raised some questions in Washington about the extent to
which the United States and Israel are singing from the same sheet.
</P>
<P>
Barak also floated ideas about making changes to the Wye
agreement which Clinton painstakingly mediated last October
between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
"Full implementation now is too risky," Barak told the New York
Times. "It would reduce our chances of achieving a permanent peace.
"
</P>
<P>
He said he favored either partial implementation or
amalgamating various Israeli withdrawals from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
But the United States insisted that the Wye agreement be
implemented quickly without any changes.
</P>
<P>
"We're not suggesting that the agreement should be changed, "
State Department spokesman James Rubin said. "On the Contrary, we
think that both sides should implement the agreement, period, full
stop ... It can and should be implemented now."
</P>
<P>
All these have cast some damper on euphoria for a quick revival
and fulfilling of the peace process in the Middle East. 
</P>
</TEXT>
