<DOCNO> XIE19990715.0307 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Further Refutes Cox Report (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Zhao said that the Cox Report surmised, very subjectively, that
China wanted to acquire U.S. thermonuclear weapons codes so as to
develop new nuclear weapons. The report even claimed that China
has acquired some U.S. computer codes, including MCNPT code, the
DOT3.5 code, and the NJOYC code.
</P>
<P>
"In fact, the three codes are standard ones extensively used
worldwide for decades in nuclear reactor engineering design,
nuclear reactor radiation shielding safety analysis and other
fields of nuclear energy research," Zhao said, "they have nothing
to do with the design of thermonuclear warhead."
</P>
<P>
In order to promote the development of China's nuclear power
construction, China in early 1980s acquired gratis from the
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) the three codes as other
member countries did.
</P>
<P>
The research results and computer software developed by Chinese
scientists have also been frequently provided to the IAEA to be
shared by other member countries. The concoctors of the Cox Report
slandered China for "illegally" acquiring computer software codes
to develop its own nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
This only exposes an ignorance of general scientific and
technical knowledge," Zhao said.
</P>
<P>
"It is sheer nonsense that the report alleged China 'stole' the
secrets of the nuclear explosion tests of miniature fusion from
the United States," he said.
</P>
<P>
Wang Ganchang, a noted Chinese physicist and academician of the
Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS), initially advanced the concept
of laser-based nuclear fusion as early as in 1964, when China
successfully exploded its first atom bomb. Wang was one of the
first scientists in the world who have independently put forward
the concept.
</P>
</TEXT>
