<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Further Refutes Cox Report (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Yu Min, a renowned Chinese theoretical physicist and CAS
academician, and a team of Chinese scientists advanced the concept
of achieving laser fusion through the method of the X-ray
radiation for driving by shooting laser into a heavy metal shelled
cavity through the entrance, Zhao said.
</P>
<P>
He added that Yu and his partners also put forward the
structural design of placing target pellets at the center of the
columnar hollow cavity.
</P>
<P>
China manufactured its own laser device, known by "Shen Guang"
(magic light), for research into laser-based nuclear fusion at the
turn of 1970s and 1980s.
</P>
<P>
The Cox Report assaulted that China "stole" or "illegally
acquired" U.S. missile technology through commercial satellite
launches in order to improve its own missiles.
</P>
<P>
"People with even slight knowledge of science and technology
would know that a carrier rocket is developed on the basis of
ballistic missiles," Zhao said, "The carrier rocket and missile
have different requirements in terms of guidance precision."
</P>
<P>
The guidance of a rocket was mainly for controlling the orbital
injection precision of satellite, while a missile's guidance
system was to control the deviation during its three major phases
of flight, the powered and unpowered flight phases and the re-
entry phase, so as to ultimately achieve pinpoint accuracy in
delivering the warhead on the selected target.
</P>
<P>
"It is obvious that a missile requires greater precision in the
guidance system than a carrier rocket," Zhao said, "The greater
the precision of a commercial satellite launch, the higher the
cost."
</P>
<P>
Generally speaking, commercial launches did not require
excessively high guidance technology considering economic
rationality. "How can one use the rocket guidance technology for
improving the guidance precision of missiles?" Zhao questioned. (
more)
nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990715.0310 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Further Refutes Cox Report (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Cox Report also said that China has acquired U.S. carrier
rocket fairing technique through commercial satellite launches,
which "may assist the design and improve reliability of future PRC
MIRVed missiles and of future submarine-launched ballistic
missiles".
</P>
<P>
"The fact is that prior to 1992, China had developed two kinds
of fairing, and succeeded in many launches under wind aloft
conditions in winter season," Zhao said.
</P>
<P>
"What deserves special mention is that a distinct difference
exists between the design technology of the fairing on a carrier
rocket and that of a multiple-warhead missile," he added, "the
fairing of a multi-warhead missile requires an all-climate, omni-
bearing operating environment, which generally results in an
integrated design."
</P>
<P>
The technique of lateral separation design, however, was
normally used for carrier rockets. Therefore, it was out of the
question to make use of the rocket's fairing design technique for
improving that of a multiple-warhead missile, Zhao said.
</P>
<P>
Zhao said that the Cox Report also largely misrepresented the
investigation about the Intelsat708 satellite launch failure by a
Long March-3B on February 15, 1996. The report claimed that it was
under the direction of U.S. experts of the independent Review
Committee (IRC) that the Chinese found the key cause for the
failure and "illegally obtained" U.S. technology out of process.
</P>
<P>
"In fact, the cause of the failure was independently found by
Chinese scientists," he said, "The reason came from the quality of
the welding of the electronic device in the follow-up frame loop
of the rocket inertia platform. Such a low-level problem has
nothing to do with the design and improvement of the rocket." (
more)

nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990715.0311 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Further Refutes Cox Report (5) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Zhao pointed out that the Chinese side's investigation lasted
for five months, with a great deal of testing demonstrations.
During the IRC's four actual work days, the February 15 failure
investigation was still in stage of analyzing and verifying the
failure mode, and a great deal of testing work of the sub-systems,
parts and components remained to be done. "How could people
localize the details of the final fault spot up to the component
in advance?"
</P>
<P>
There was no more absurd part in the Cox Report than Chapter
VII about the launch site security in China. Cox and his ilk
collected and enumerated a lot of so-called materials and details
in an attempt to prove that China "stole" the U.S. technology.
Having no evidence, they had to apply terms of conjecture such as
"if", "perhaps" to mislead the public.
</P>
<P>
Zhao gave several examples to show the U.S. side's strict
control over U.S.-made satellites. At the satellite test and
filling buildings, control rooms and the operation platform on the
launch tower, 18 American-controlled video cameras were installed
for around-the-clock monitoring of the satellites and test
equipment. "No videotapes can prove that the Chinese had any
access to the U.S.-made satellites," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
In the satellite working area of the test building alone, four
video cameras were pointed at the satellites from different angles.
</P>
<P>
Zhao mentioned in particular that likewise, since the U.S. side
's reinforced monitoring of the U.S.-made satellites would affect
the technology safety of China's re-entry vehicle, the Chinese
side had to implement 24-hour monitoring of its rockets as well. (
more)


nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
