<HEADLINE> Vietnam not to Accept U.S. Trying to Apply its Law Outside its Borders: Foreign Ministry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam said it will not accept the
United States trying to apply its law outside its own borders,
saying that this violates the basic principle of international law
on equality among nations.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of Vietnam's Foreign Ministry and the U.S.
State Department have held extra talks on human rights and
religious affairs, according to the Press and Information
Department of the Vietnamese Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The talks, following a seventh round last month, were held
during a four-day visit to Vietnam from July 11 to 14 by U.S.
Deputy Assistant Secretary of State Bennett Freeman and U.S.
ambassador at Large for Religious Freedom Robert Seiple.
</P>
<P>
The two Americans met with Chairman of the Vietnamese
government Commission for Religious Affairs Le Quang Vinh;
Chairwoman of Vietnam's National Assembly's Commission for
Culture, Education, Youth and Children Tran Thi Tam Dan; and
Vietnam's Deputy Foreign Minister Nguyen Dinh Bin.
</P>
<P>
The Americans explained the purpose of the International
Religious Freedom Law passed by the U.S. Congress and approved by
U.S. President Bill Clinton in October 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese officials explained their country's policy of
allowing freedom of belief.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese side re-affirmed that the principle of dialogue
is respecting independence and sovereignty and non-interference in
the internal affairs of other countries as well as cooperation for
mutual benefit.
</P>
<P>
The American side expressed their appreciation of Vietnam's
cooperation in finding their countrymen missing in action (MIAs)
during Vietnam war.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese side demanded U.S. cooperation in dealing with
the aftermath left by the Americans during the Vietnam war,
including the chemical toxic Agent Orange sprayed by U.S.
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The talks were said to be "candid, constructive and
contributive" to mutual understanding.
</P>
<P>
The Americans ended their visit on Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
