<HEADLINE> Britain Takes Lead in Admiral'Cup Sailing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Britain took a lead in the Admiral'
s Cup sailing on Wednesday after an opening day filled with chaos
and collisions, according to reports from Cowes, England.
</P>
<P>
Even before the weather had a chance to take its toll off the
Isle of Wight coast, France quit the competition and then rejoined
with a smaller team to add high drama to the unofficial world
championship of off-shore racing.
</P>
<P>
The United States, defending titlist, shared fifth-place with
Australia in the aggregate standings.
</P>
<P>
The Admiral's Cup commenced with behind the scenes wrangling
which forced France to initially withdraw in a row over an illegal
mast on one of its three boats.
</P>
<P>
France rejoined the competition with its remaining two boats,
resulting in several difficult clashes for the three-boat U.S.
team.
</P>
<P>
There is six races remaining for the U.S. to defend the Admiral
's Cup it won in 1997, which was America's first win in the event
for 28 years.
</P>
<P>
Host nation Britain leads, followed by a composite European
team with the Netherlands in No. 3 spot and Germany in No. 4, just
ahead of the United States and Australia.
</P>
<P>
Italy, the combined Commonwealth team fills seventh and eighth
places with France trailing in last place. 
</P>
</TEXT>
