<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Menem Hails Agreement Between Argentina and Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Argentine President Carlos
Menem on Wednesday hailed the agreement signed between his country
and Britain as a great step to resume flights to the Malvinas
islands.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference in the government house, Menem said that
the agreement will clear the way for further talks and dialogues
between Argentina and Britain.
</P>
<P>
The first direct flight from Argentina will take off on October
16 and the parents of the victims in the conflict with Britain
will be the first Argentines to travel to the islands since 1982
war, in which 652 Argentine soldiers were killed. If possible,
Menem said, he himself will be among the first travelers.
</P>
<P>
Menem said that he is confident that Argentines to visit the
Malvinas islands will not have to bear a passport in the future,
signifying a return to the conditions which prevailed before 1982.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed in London by Argentine Foreign
Minister Guido Di Tella and his British counterpart Robin Cook.
</P>
<P>
Menem has previously stated that he believes Argentina will
resume the exercise of the sovereignty over the Malvinas islands
before the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
