<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Bank Recapitalization to Cost Half GDP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The cost for restructuring and
recapitalizing the country's battered banking sector was estimated
at 550 trillion rupiah (about 82 billion U.S. dollars), or about
50 percent of the gross domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
Minister of Finance Bambang Subianto said the burden to the
state budget in the next fiscal year beginning from April 2000
would be much higher than the 34 trillion rupiah (about 5.07
billion dollars) allocated in the current 1999/2000 budget.
</P>
<P>
"The burden to the budget in the next fiscal year will be
greater, but we're still calculating it," Bambang was quoted by
The Jakarta Post Thursday as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said lessening the burden on the state budget depended on
how successful the monetary authority was in lowering domestic
interest rates and checking inflation.
</P>
<P>
The central bank's benchmark interest rate dropped to 15.86
percent on Wednesday from 35 percent earlier this year. The
interest rate on Bank Indonesia's three-month promissory note also
dropped, falling to 15.66 percent from 23.33 percent.
</P>
<P>
The central bank has allowed interest rates to fall on the back
of a stronger rupiah and lower inflation.
</P>
<P>
The government is issuing bonds to finance the bank
restructuring and recapitalization program. The bonds will carry a
fixed interest rate and a floating rate linked to the interest
rate on the three-month promissory note.
</P>
<P>
The government has so far issued 157.61 trillion rupiah (23.52
billion dollars) worth of bonds, of which 103.8 trillion rupiah
(15.49 billion dollars) was allocated for the recapitalization of
seven private banks, four nationalized banks and 12 provincial
development banks. The remaining 53.81 trillion rupiah (8.03
billion dollars) will be used to repay money the government
borrowed from the central bank to bail out banks last year.
</P>
<P>
The government plans further bond issues, 233.25 trillion
rupiah (34.78 billion dollars) of which will be used to
recapitalize the country's seven state banks.
</P>
<P>
The state budget will carry the cost of the bonds' interest
rate, which in the current fiscal year is estimated at 34 trillion
rupiah (5.07 billion dollars). The Indonesian Bank Restructuring
Agency (IBRA) is responsible for half of this amount.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia hopes to complete bank restructuring by the end of
the year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
