<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 23,000 Tons of Banana Destroyed in Costa Rica </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Costa Rica-based North
American Company, Standard Fruit, confirmed on Wednesday that it
has destroyed more than 23,000 tons of bananas in the shadow of
excessive production.
</P>
<P>
The banana market has been plagued since last April by
overproduction, which has spurred a 50-percent drop in the market
prices.
</P>
<P>
The price of a box containing 18.14 kilograms of bananas has
fallen from 12.50 dollars to only 6.75 dollars on the U.S. market.
In the European Union, where the prices have traditionally been
much higher, the price has fallen from 20.7 dollars last year to
the current 12.6 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Producers find that they could hardly cover the production
costs and have decided to leave part of the produce on the farms.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman from Standard Fruit, Juan Carlos Rojas, said that
the company has chosen not to export 300,000 boxes of bananas from
independent producers, in addition to 1 million boxes produced by
the company.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Trade Minister Samuel Guzowsky visited Brussels last
week to negotiate a new banana import rule with the European
Commission. He said Wednesday that the producer companies are
experiencing a "very serious" situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
