<HEADLINE> East China Province Sees Rise In Foreign Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Foreign trade in east China's
Shandong Province grew four percent to hit 8.32 billion U.S.
dollars in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
Exports reached 5.18 billion dollars, a 5.2 percent rise on a
yearly basis, while imports climbed 0.3 percent to garner 3.14
billion dollars, according to latest statistics released by the
provincial trade authorities.
</P>
<P>
Breaking down the figures, exports to Japan and the Republic of
Korea (ROK) went up an impressive 15 percent each, a growth rate
higher than the 1998 level. And total exports to the United States
and the European Union maintained steady growth.
</P>
<P>
During the January-June period, the province added 724 overseas-
funded enterprises, using 1.33 billion dollars of contractual
overseas investment or up 28 percent over same period last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990715.0364 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China Province to Restructure Foreign Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, July 15 (Xinhua) -- East China's Shandong Province, one
of the country's economic powerhouses, will expand export of
technology and service to balance its commodity-dominated trade
structure.
</P>
<P>
Provincial Governor Li Chunting said the decision is part of
his province's effort to restructure its foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
Shandong now has economic and trade ties with more than 180
countries and regions. Local foreign trade has grown by 15.9
percent annually in the past two decades, with exports rising 13.4
percent per year.
</P>
<P>
The province's imports and exports reached 16.6 billion U.S.
dollars in 1998, accounting for 22.5 percent of local GDP.
</P>
<P>
However, the governor said, the province's imports and exports
have been focused on commodities, with investment, technology and
service making up only a very small amount of the foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
"This lopsidedness of trade is unfavorable to the sound
development of the local economy," Li said.
</P>
<P>
According to Li, the province will take measures to increase
technology and service exports. Meanwhile, it will expand
cooperation with multinational trade partners in a bid to gain a
footing in the global sales market.
</P>
<P>
Local enterprises are encouraged to get involved in foreign
trade directly by establishing production lines in other countries.
</P>
<P>
The province will also try to contract more engineering and
labor projects abroad.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
