<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chile Timber Exports Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Chile's timber exports throughout
the first five months of the year rose by 4.7 percent to 738.9
million U.S. dollars, compared with the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Executive Director of the National Forestry Corporation (CONAF)
Cristian Palma said Wednesday that the production of the timber
products with higher average prices surged.
</P>
<P>
These items include moldings, battens, locks, doors, windows
and frames, which account for around 30 percent of the total
exports.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the increase of the timber exports have spurred
the Chilean forestry industry.
</P>
<P>
The United States is still the largest importer of the Chilean
timber products with the turnover of 171.3 million dollars, an
increase of 26.7 percent, compared with the January-May period of
last year, said Palma.
</P>
<P>
Japan stood at the second place with 105.9 million dollars,
which represents a fall of 3.7 per cent compared with the same
period in 1998.
</P>
<P>
South Korea held the third place, with 45.4 million dollars, an
increase of 52.6 per cent over last year.
</P>
<P>
China is in the fourth place, with 44.3 million dollars,
followed by Belgium with 43.6 million dollars and Italy with 41.5
million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990715.0367 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
