<HEADLINE> Brazil's Record Grain Harvest Predicted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Brazil's grain harvest during the
1998-1999 period will be 82.117 million tons, 7.3 percent higher
than the 1997-1998 period, said Minister of Agriculture Francisco
Turra Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The National Supply Company associated with the Ministry of
Agriculture estimated that the bean harvest will increase by 34.7
percent over last year and the rice harvest by 35.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The cotton harvest is predicted to increase by 22.7 percent,
oats by 18.1 percent, maize by 6.8 percent and flour by 6.1
percent.
</P>
<P>
The crop cultivation area rose by 4.5 percent in comparison
with the 1997-1998 period. At the same time, the ministry also
predicted a 12 percent growth rate for grapes, 4.6 percent for
apples, and 46 percent for coffee.
</P>
<P>
The rise in coffee production will raise Brazil's share to 27
percent in the world output.
</P>
<P>
President of the company Benmedito Rosa believed that Brazil's
harvest will continue to rise this year as 20 percent more loans
will be provided for agricultural projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
