<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cell Causing Hodgkin's Lymphoma Discovered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 14 (Xinhua) -- A group of American
researchers have discovered the cell that causes Hodgkin's
lymphoma, a disease affecting more than 58,000 people worldwide
per year.
</P>
<P>
Human Genome Sciences (HGSI), a company aimed at discovering
and understanding human and microbial genes, said in a report
Wednesday that in making the discovery, scientists from the
company and other organizations applied new methods to a single
cancer cell to reveal that the Reed-Sternberg cell, the cause of
the disease, originates in B cells, a type of immune cell that
normally produces antibodies.
</P>
<P>
The discovery is described in the July 15 issue of Blood.
</P>
<P>
According to HGSI, the abnormal Reed-Sternberg cell of
Hodgkin's lymphoma has been recognized to be responsible for the
disease. But characterization of the cell itself is difficult as
fewer than one in 1,000 cells of the lymphoma are cancer cells
themselves. The great majority of cell in the lymphoma are normal
immune cells that react to the few cancer cells present in the
tumor.
</P>
<P>
The origin of the Reed-Sternberg cell has been debated ever
since the cell was discovered a century ago. The current study
made two advances in solving the mystery. First micro-dissection
methods made it possible to isolate the Reed-Sternberg cells from
patients' tumor tissues. Second, ultra high-throughput sequence
analysis was used to identify the genes present in the cells. The
study determined a total of more than 11 million nucleotide
sequences, representing 27,000 genes. Then powerful computer
programs were used to compare these genes of the Reed-Sternber
cell with those used in normal human cells.
</P>
<P>
The study provides a clue to why the Reed-Sternberg cells cause
cancer. Normal cells of the immune system contain a self-destruct
system that cause them to die when they begin to grow out of
control. Critical components of the self-destruct system are
missing in the Reed-Sternberg cell.
</P>
<P>
HGSI said that the discovery opens new hope for early diagnosis
and treatment of the disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
