<HEADLINE> European Integration Stalls Italy's South Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, 14 July (Xinhua) -- European integration, widely thought
to be the key to Italy's economic future, is stalling the growth
of the southern regions, a government agency said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to Svimez, the Italian southern development research
agency, "closer ties between the economies of the fifteen European
countries means that the south is having to face competition from
the rest of the EU."
</P>
<P>
The government agency said that the Italian state had not taken
enough measures to invest in the south, and the divide between
north and south was therefore widening.
</P>
<P>
According to the analysis of figures released by Svimez, 1998
was a good year for production, investments and employment in the
south, although the overall picture isn't as good.
</P>
<P>
Svimez said the south's economic results were "not good enough
to change the way things stood in the 1990s."
</P>
<P>
Svimez said that from 1992 to 1998, overall growth in the south
had only reached 2.9 percent, which was less than a third of
growth in the north.
</P>
<P>
It noted that in 1998, unemployment in the south stood at 22.8
percent, a 7 percent increase over 1992. Unemployment in the north
and center of Italy reached 7.4 percent, compared to 6.5 percent
in 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
