<HEADLINE> U.N. Sends Team to Zambia to Prepare for Congo (K) Truce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 14 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan is dispatching a three-person team to Lusaka, capital of
Zambia, to work with Zambian President Frederic Chiluba who is
trying to bring rebels to sign the peace accord for Congo (K), a
U.N. spokesman announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general is still prepared to send a full-fledged
technical team to Congo (K) upon the full signing of the peace
agreement, Manoel de Almeida e Silva said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council Monday urged rebel leaders in Congo
(K) to sign the ceasefire accord, a condition before any
peacekeepers would be sent to the central African country.
</P>
<P>
Six African nations involved in the 11-month-long conflict
signed on Saturday last week in Lusaka, but rebel groups refused
to do so because of a split within their ranks.
</P>
<P>
Annan is expected to recommend the Security Council approve of
a peacekeeping force of up to 20,000 soldiers, mainly drawn from
African countries.
</P>
<P>
The complicated conflict in Congo (K) pits rebels in the east,
backed by neighboring Rwanda and Uganda, against President Laurent
Kabila, who was supported by troops from Zimbabwe, Chad, Angola
and Namibia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
