<HEADLINE> U.N. Meeting on Peaceful Uses of Outer Space </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Committee on the
Peaceful Uses of Outer Space started a three-day session in Vienna
Wednesday, to finalize preparations for a U.N. conference on the
similar topics.
</P>
<P>
The Committee session is tackling issues like space debris and
international space law, U.N. spokesman Manoel de Almeida e Silva
said.
</P>
<P>
The aim is to develop a blueprint for the peaceful uses of
outer space in the next century, he added.
</P>
<P>
According to U.N. information, an estimated 8,500 objects
classifiable as space debris are cruising in the geostationary
orbit and low-Earth atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
Ways of minimizing the impact of space debris on space missions
is a priority for the U.N. Committee.
</P>
<P>
This becomes especially important when objects with nuclear
power sources aboard are taken into consideration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
