<HEADLINE> U.S. Hopes Wye Accord Implemented with Changes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on
Wednesday that it hopes the Wye agreement, reached last October
between Israel and the Palestinians, would be carried out without
changes.
</P>
<P>
"We're not suggesting that the agreement should be changed,"
State Department spokesman James Rubin said at a regular
briefing. "On the contrary, we think that both sides should
implement the agreement ... It can and should be implemented now."
</P>
<P>
Rubin was reacting to Israel's new Prime Minister Ehud Barak
who said he favored either partial implementation or
amalgamating various Israel withdrawals from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
"Full implementation now is too risky," he told the New York
Times in an interview on the eve of his departure to Washington.
"It would reduce our chances of achieving a permanent peace."
</P>
<P>
To the Washington Post, he said it would be preferable to
stage Israel's withdrawal from Palestinian areas in one big step
as part of a single peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
The Wye agreement, under which Israel would pull out of 13
percent of more territory from the West Bank, was suspended last
December by former Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration was eager to see the agreement
fully carried out so as to push peace process in the Middle East
forward.
</P>
<P>
Rubin indicated small amendments could be made but on the
condition that both Israel and the Palestinians would accept
them.
</P>
<P>
"If there is some desire to make modest adjustments and both
sides agree to them we would not stand in the way of that. But
in the meantime it is our view that the agreement should be
implemented as signed," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
