<DOCNO> XIE19990715.0384 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2.5 Million Italian Family Live in Poverty, Report Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, 14 July (Xinhua) -- More than 2.5 million families in
Italy are considered poor, Italian National Statistics Bureau
Istat declared in a report Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Istat defines a two-member family as poor if it spends less per
month than the national average per capita.
</P>
<P>
The cut-off for 1998 was 1,476 million lire (about 775 U.S.
dollars) a month, up from 1,430 million lire in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Istat said that 7,423 million individuals, equivalent to 11.8
percent of the population, lived below the poverty line.
</P>
<P>
It noted that 65 out of every 100 poor families lived on the
southern peninsula, Sicily or Sardinia, and said that large
families were more likely to be affected, with 22.7 percent of
families of five or more considered poor, the figure rising to 34
percent in the south.
</P>
<P>
Levels of education also seemed to have an effect on living
conditions, with poverty affecting 18.7 percent of families whose
main breadwinner did not have a university degree, whereas only
0.9 percent of families of graduates were considered poor in the
north, 3.1 percent in central Italy and 8.2 percent in the south.
</P>
<P>
Istat declared, however, that the overall situation in southern
and northern regions had improved slightly compared to the
previous year, but noted a worsening of conditions in central
Italy.
</P>
<P>
Italian Social Affairs Minister Liva Turco declared that a fund
of at least 1 trillion lire ( about 520 million U.S. dollars)
would be set up to fight poverty in the country.
</P>
<P>
On hand when Istat statistics on poverty were released, Turco
said the fact that poverty had fallen slightly in 1998 was an
encouraging sign, but noted that "the fight against poverty
remains one of the center-left government's top priorities."
</P>
<P>
She said the government intended to follow through on its
financial aid plan for large families. Turco also called for more
measures to be taken to improve public services as well as for a
more positive employment policy towards women. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
